animal.description:
Adoption Fee: $250
Fostered in Indian Trail, North Carolina
Age: 8 years
Weight: 7 lbs.

8/5/20 - Bubbles is doing really well right now.  Her prognosis after her relapse was very guarded because usually pups do not fair well when a relapse occurs.  She is pretty much back to her normal self, bossy and going at the others if they do something she does not approve of.  Bubbles will always need to be under the care of a specialist.  She is currently on prednisone every other day and a chemo drug every other day, which will likely be for the protocol for the rest of her time.  She sees the specialist when she is not feeling well and then every couple months bloodwork and to make sure everything is still ok.  The chemo drug can cause other problems, hence the reason for continued care with her specialist.

10/24/19 -  Bubbles is having some GI issues again.  She has been throwing up for a week or two and none of the anti-nausea meds have been helping.  She had an ultrasound today and her pancreas looked inflamed and portions of her intestines looked inflamed as well.  Her bloodwork was also indicative of GI issues.  Her belly also filled with fluid yesterday and has not gone down.  The liquid is clear and likely her body storing water.  We are starting her on a round of steroids and antibiotics and will wait for the review of the ultrasound by a radiologist And some additional bloodwork and urine check.  She may need an endoscopy or biopsy to get a better idea of what is going on, but we need to wait for the inflammation to go down and her to feel better before doing so.  

4/15/19 – Bubbles is still the same little girl!  She has been doing great on her prescription food and has not had any issues.  She does still have moments where she loses her self confidence and will bite, we say she is like Jekyll and Hyde.  She will also go after the other dogs if she does not want them around or is protecting a bone or toy or spot on the couch.  She can also be very loving and happy and wanting all the attention she can get.  She just has her moments sometimes. 

 7/5/16 ? Bubbles is still feisty as ever. She loves to play with her foster brothers, she just isn?t so sure about humans sometimes. She can be so happy and friendly with people and want attention and then all of the sudden becomes insecure and scared and snaps. Being on her prescription food and Pepcid has taken care of all her tummy issues and she seems a bit happier now too. She is prone to bite more when she is not feeling well, which is understandable since people get cranky when they do not feel good too. She needs a home that can understand her fears and handle them and it would be great if there was another dog about her size and age to play with too.


5/4/15 - Bubbles recently had some medical issues and spent a good bit of time at the vet, but after several tests it was found that she has irritable bowel disorder. She is on Prednisone, Pepcid, Anti-Nausea medicine and a prescription diet. Thankfully this has solved her throwing up and diarrhea and she is back to her happy loving self. Although she can be happy and loving and very playful, she does have the other side of her where she has bitten. When she loses her self confidence and becomes unsure of the situation she has bitten and has drawn blood. Her foster parents have learned to read her behaviors to know when this may happen and have worked around it. She does better one on one with people instead of having multiple people giving her attention. She does love belly rubs, playing with people and other pups, and exploring the back yard. She absolutely loves her prescription diet and tells you when you are not getting it done fast enough for her. Bubbles would do best in a home with young pups, no children, and people who understand her personality quarks and can let her grow and learn in a safe environment and do not mind the occasional snap when she becomes unsure of the situation or unsure of herself.


5/22/2014 - Bubbles loves chilling in a nice comfy bed or on the couch, running around the yard with the other pups yelling at the neighbor dogs, and on occasion plays with other pups in her foster home. She is an excellent eater and likes to chew on bones. She is a very loving and happy little girl. At times she gets a bit of an attitude and wants to only do what she wants to do and does not hesitate to let you know.

12/24/2013 - My story is the story of  "The Princess to The Pauper"!

In my previous life, I was the only furchild of a single, elderly lady who loved me unconditionally. We did everything together, went to the post office, watched tv, ate dinner and slept in the bed! When my Mom passed away, I was given to her daughter and grandson to live. This is where things got a little tricky.

I had become so accustomed to my simple-spoiled life that I had a hard time adjusting. I just didn't like all the commotion associated with young people coming and going in and out of the house. I was afraid and wanted my simple, quiet, spoiled rotten life back,as one can understand.
After two months, I was given up on, thrown out and taken to the local animal shelter. So as you can see, I went from "The Princess to The Pauper".

Things got much worse for me at the shelter because I was put into a single 4x6 room with concrete floors and cylinder block walls. I was terrified, so terrified in fact that I growled at the animal control officers and would try to bite them. They labeled me "Devil Dog".

Thank goodness Yorkie Haven Rescue learned of my terrible situation and came to rescue me. I was given to my Foster Mommy in a crate and driven straight to my Foster home. Foster Mommy took me outside and let me out of my crate. I jumped straight in her lap, tail wagging, and placed a big ole wet kiss right on her nose!

Foster Mommy says I am a good girl, very loyal and protective. She also calls me an alpha female, whatever that means! I went to the dogtor the next day and had a perfectly clean bill of health. The next day we were off to the groomer to get a nice bath and haircut. Whew! I feel like a new woman!!!
In my Foster home there are two other female yorkies and a 2 year old human child, all three of which I am NOT A FAN! I would prefer to be the only baby in the house...that means no other doggies or children to take away from my attention.

If you are looking for a lifelong, loyal, lapdog- I am the girl for you!

Sending you tail wags and kisses!
Bubbles
Bub

animal.description:
DEE DEE is a lovable 2-year-old, 55-pound, Black Labrador Retriever and Hound mix who's got some big ideas!

"Say, I was thinking. If we could figure out a way to spend some quality time together, there are so many cool things I could show you. For example, did you know that there's a dog beach in Asbury Park?  Dogs are allowed on the Boardwalk and on the 8th avenue Dog Beach all day between 9/15 and 5/15.  It's a really nice place to go in the cool weather, especially at night!  I could show it to you! Have you ever hiked up at Ramapo Mountain State Forest?  That's another cool place I could take you, there are so many beautiful trails, (and fall foliage is coming!), you can even hike up to some ruins!  I'll bet you think you know your neighborhood like the back of your hand, but you've never walked it with me, I'll show you all kinds of cool stuff that you probably never noticed before!  Do you like going for rides?  I dig rides!  If you'll drive, I'll ride shotgun, we can go on road trips together or maybe some snack runs on movie night! There's so much fun stuff we could do,  I'm getting excited just thinking about it!

You know, I think I may have figured out a way.  FOSTER to ADOPT!  We could try it!  If you'll come to HQ and get me, I can come and stay at your house for a few days or even a week or two if you want. It would be like a really long sleepover! Doesn't that sound like fun?  Oh, one more thing, do you know how to give a belly rub?

Oh man, I can't wait 'til you get here!"  ~Dee Dee

WHAT'S NEXT?

If you would like to foster, foster-to-adopt, (in case you're not sure), or adopt sweet DEE DEE, just fill out our online FOSTER/ADOPTION APPLICATION, which can be found in the main menu of our website or at the bottom of this page - simply copy and paste the link into your browser. EASY PEASY!

Once we've reviewed your application, arrangements can be made for you guys to meet! It'll be kind of like a blind date!

***

This pet is spayed or neutered in accordance with our strict policy wherein Yoall animals are altered prior to adoption. This pet is dewormed, current on vaccines, and started on monthly flea/tick and preventatives.

Animal Alliance's policy is that we will adopt dogs younger than 1 year old to families with children under 9 years old. We do not adopt dogs 1 year or older to families with children under 9 years old due to the unknown history of adult dogs. 

Prior to submitting an application, please see the Animal Alliance Adoption Process for adoption details.

To fill out an adoption application, go to:
https://www.animalalliancenj.org/fosteradoption-application/

GORGEOUS PRINCESS ANNA WOULD LOVE TO BE IN A FOSTER HOME WHILE SHE WAITS FOR HER FOREVER FAMILY TO FIND HER. IF YOU ARE INTERESTED IN FOSTERING PRINCESS ANNA, GO TO THE MAKE A DIFFERENCE RESCUE FACEBOOK PAGE AND SEND A PRIVATE MESSAGE THAT INCLUDES YOUR PHONE NUMBER AND EMAIL ADDRESS.

Princess Anna is a 5.5 year old Cattle Dog mix. Princess Anna was a pregnant stray wandering the streets. Make A Difference Rescue was notified about her and we quickly rescued her. She had her babies in February 2018 just before Valentine's day. Princess Anna is now ready to start the next chapter of her life. She is a very sweet and gentle girl. Princess Anna loves to go for walks, go for car rides or just hang out with people. Children 7 years old or older. She is good with other dogs after a proper introduction is done. Unfortunately, we do not know how she is with cats. Her forever home must have a fenced yard where she can safely run and play. Princess Anna is spayed, up to date on her vaccinations, on monthly heart worm preventative as well as house and crate trained. Princess cannot wait to be part of a very loving family!!

All dogs we rescue stay with us until they find their forever homes. We do not do same day adoptions. A home visit is required to ensure our dog is going to a safe environment and our dog gets along with your dog(s) and/or cat(s). We require all our dogs over the age of 1 year attend 1 obedience class (6 week session) outside the home. You must live within 1 hour of Birmingham, MI to adopt one of our dogs. No out of state or outside the U.S. adoptions or fosters.  Princess Anna's adoption fee is $275.

animal.description:
If you are looking for a guy who will be your snuggle buddy, Tucker is IT!  He loves nothing more than to be the center of your universe!  He is living at our sanctuary and when he gets his turn at being in the living room he expects that he will get your undivided attention and makes it clear to all who are with him.  If someone chooses to be on the computer instead, he will tolerate it for a while but then he will come over and gently lay his head on their arm and remind them of who is the priority!

Should it be his turn in one of the exercise yards he forgets all about snuggling and is all about the balls!  He is learning that he can trade for a second ball and give up the one that he has.  Tucker is very smart, has gone thru  our Companions I and II classes and enjoys showing his skills to all who will watch.  

If Tucker could answer the question of where he would like to live I suspect it would go something like this-"I want to be the only dog in the house and I certainly do not want to share my space with a cat!!  I'll share a couch but I want my own crate!  A fenced in yard is my happy place!"  He does need experienced dog owners, adults or teens.  

Because he needs a fenced in yard and needs to be the only animal, a single family home is also going to fit him best.  He would not be a good fit for an apartment or a condo.  


Some stats on this guy-he is 74 lbs., and is 8 years old, is crate trained.

Call us at Our Companions Animal Rescue and Sanctuary at 860-242-9999 or e-mail to daryl@ourcompanions.org to get more information on Tucker!!  You can also go to www.ourcompanions.org and see more pictures and more description of him on the adoption page!

Meet Coco!

Coco is a sweet love bug who looking to be someone’s best friend. Need a running partner? Coco is your girl. Want someone to warm your side while you mellow on the couch and watch TV? Coco can do that too. She has such a big heart and is ready to steal yours. Who doesn’t want to come home to a big bundle of love who acts like you coming home is the best present they’ve ever received?

An energetic dog, Coco would do best in a home with a yard with a privacy fence where she can run. It may take her a bit to warm to other dogs, but once she does, they are her best friends and she loves to play. Her favorite past times are walks, tug of warm and wrestling, though she can be a couch potato when she feels like it. For the previous reasons, Coco would also do well in a home with other dogs and older children. While she doesn’t mean to, she may be too strong and outgoing for smaller children. She also is a leash puller, so she will need someone who can handle her strength.

Coco has no issues going into her kennel when needed, is gentle about taking treats, and is not food aggressive. That being said, if she can reach it, she will take it if given the chance. She may have been picked up as a stray but she behaves well and learns quickly. She responds best to audible cues rather than words. That being said, she would do best in a home with someone who can be patient with her while she learns to navigate her way in the world. 


Our Adoption Process: 
*You must complete an adoption application before meeting an animal.
*We do all checks on references and vet checks.  
*Please let your references know we will be calling. 
*Once approved, you can set up an appointment to meet any of the animals at the Granite City Animal Control, or the ones in foster homes. 
*There will be a meet and greet and then a home visit.
*After that you will sign an adoption contract and pay the adoption fee.  

$85 for Rabbits / $80 for Cats / $100 Kittens / $150 for Dogs / $200 for Puppies Six Months & Under

The dog adoption application is located here:
https://form.jotform.com/31997643682166

All our animals are completely vetted with the required vaccinations, microchipped and spayed/neutered before leaving the rescue. 
Including: 
Cats will have FIV/FeLV testing
Dogs will have Heartworm testing
Rabbits will have a wellness check 

______________________________________________________________


Many times we also get feral cats or semi-friendly cats (can be petted but doesn't like to be held) needing barn homes. You will need to provide shelter and food. There are not any adoption fees for barn cats (donations are accepted) but you will still need to fill out the cat adoption form. Just list the number of barn cats you are wanting.  

______________________________________________________________

We are a small foster based rescue but some of our animals are residing at the Granite City Animal Control in Madison County, Illinois until they can be adopted, fostered or pulled by another rescue. 

Pound Pets Inc Rescue can always use more fosters.
If you are interested in fostering, the foster application is located here:

https://form.jotform.com/50784968756173

______________________________________________________________

Pound Pets volunteers cleans the animal control building, we are the caregivers for the animals brought in. Once they come through the door, they become our responsibility. We photograph all animals and post to the Pound Pets Facebook page. We provide them clean kennels, beds, blankets, toys, treats, outside play time, walks and human interaction. We try to comfort the scared, keep the high-energy ones exercised and provide plenty of love and affection to make their time at animal control as less stressful as possible. 

Sometimes they get reclaimed by their families and sometimes they don't. If they don't it is our responsibility to find the adopters, fosters or rescues to save them from euthanasia. 

We get in sick and injured animals as well. They do not sit in their kennels or cages needing veterinary care. Once we see the need for care they are taken to the vet. Sometimes the illness or injury is minor and the city will cover the bill, Other times when it's not, we do. We do all of this on our own dime. We buy the food, the beds, the blankets, the toys, and all the other things that go into care for the animals. Sometimes things are donated and that is wonderful!! We pay the medical bills that the city doesn't. As with most animal controls, there is a limit on what they will do or cover. At Pound Pets, there is no limit. Broken Bones, Surgery, Parvo, Heartworm, etc., if the animal has a chance the animal is given that chance. This is not a shelter but an animal control. 

Pound Pets Inc Rescue can always use more volunteers.
If you are interested in volunteering, the volunteer application is located here:

https://form.jotform.com/40307066949156

______________________________________________________________

We are always looking for licensed rescues to pull cats (including FIV+ cats) and dogs from the Granite City Animal Control in Madison County, Illinois. It's a very small animal control and strays keep coming in.  There are no fees for a rescue to pull. If you can help us, please email the volunteers at poundpetsinc@gmail.com 

______________________________________________________________

Pound Pets Inc Animal Control Facebook Page:
https://www.facebook.com/poundpetsincorporated/

Pound Pets Inc Rescue Facebook Page:
https://www.facebook.com/poundpetsincrescue/

animal.description:
Sheldon is a 9-year-old, 64 pound Pitbull/basset mix. Black with white. He is house trained, however, we say that every dog needs a refresher course in their forever home. He's a friendly, lovable guy. Loves playing with toys and knows some commands, such as 'sit.' He is very smart and so much fun to hang with and play ball....one of his favorite activities.
Our teenage volunteers who spent time with him say that he is a very good dog. He just needs some work on the leash, since he's a puller. Got a definite Bassett 'bend in his front legs.' Watch his video and his fun time!
He has all his medical records, microchip - came from a home where he was much loved. His owner died of cancer, and Sheldon was so gentle when the man was in a wheelchair. He was also great with the toddler.
Please find our applications and valuable information under 'Adopt a dog'* on our website: *www.beaglesandbuddies.com* and email your application to beaglesandbuddies@gmail.com. Let us know your preference of appointment day/time and which dogs you are interested in and we will do our best to accommodate and email you the closest appointment available. Please allow us up to a week to get back to you. Most appointments will be Friday-Sunday, 10 am - 2 pm, for an hour.
*Note bring any other dog/s and the entire family to your meet and greet at B&B.* A complimentary training manual is included with each adoption, authored by terristeuben.com. Check out her website - she is fabulous!
B&B is glad to be open during the pandemic. We know the value and comfort of a loving pet companion and are doing our best to help the dogs and folks who need them. We update our website daily and are always rescuing, vetting, rehabilitating, socializing.
* We are accepting applications for volunteers to spend time with our dogs, hang out, sing/read to the shy ones, walk/toss ball with those who go to the playgrounds; cleaning, office work, gardening, and building/repair projects! *

Are you my furrever family?

For further info on the adoption process, please visit our home page and check out the "Adopt a Dog" section, which has thorough instructions. All our dogs are spayed/neutered, microchipped, and

fully vaccinated before adoption; they have been wormed, bathed, socialized, walked daily and much loved; each adoptee leaves with a leash, collar, and all medical records.

Our prices are higher than the shelters' because we nurse the dogs through their illnesses and get them needed surgeries and dentals. We also spend time socializing. Furthermore, unlike shelters, rescues do not get financial aid from the government and must rely on donations, grants, and adoption fees. Our fees for adults start at $150 and go up to $750. The higher end is for our most in demand dogs, such as young beagles and other purebred dogs. The lower end is for dogs who have been here a while. For puppies, we may go beyond this and charge $1000. The good news is that, because rescues fall under the "charity" category, the fees for our dogs are officially donations and are therefore tax deductible. You can think of it as donating to a worthy cause and getting a dog in return!

Sponsor Me

Beagles & Buddies must find ways to raise money so we can continue saving dogs. Your tax-deductible donation keeps our rescue kennel operating!

Hours

Friday: 10 am to 3 pm

Saturday: 10 am to 3 pm

Sunday: 10 am to 3 pm

Monday: CLOSED

Tuesday: CLOSED

Wednesday: CLOSED

Thursday: CLOSED



Weekday appointments may be available. We are a small staff and do our best to accommodate your needs. **Note that during COVID, we are not holding open houses on any day. Please email us for an appointment and include your application (found on our website, beaglesandbuddies.com, under "Forms"). Most appointments will be Friday through Sunday, though other days may also be available. We usually schedule one appointment per hour. Allow 1-2 hours for your appointment. Please look at our website and make a list of one or more dogs that you would like to see.

Contacting Us

If you have a question about adopting, giving up a dog, boarding, or volunteering, please visit the appropriate tabs on our
home page.

For more specific questions, call 626-444-9664 (please leave a voicemail if no answer) or email at beaglesandbuddies@gmail.com. Note that
Emailing
is always preferred!

Thanks!

Please note: If you are viewing this profile anywhere other than Beagles & Buddies own website, you are not receiving full info. Visit info on pet here.

animal.description:
Wiya is a purebred Doberman female. About 6 years old. She has not had her ears or tail cropped, and looks prettier because she is au natural.
She gets along well with other dogs and does walk on a leash but she pulls a little.  An "easy walker harness" would take care of that!

Filling out an application is the first step in the adoption process. If you have questions, the best way to contact us is to email azdesertrottis@aol.com.

We don't always bring all animals to our adoption events so check ahead of time to make sure the animal you are interested in is still available. Some animals listed may already be promised.

Arizona Desert Rotti & Pals Rescue is a NO KILL rescue serving Tucson and the surrounding area. 

We do adopt out of area under the right circumstances. If you are willing to travel to Tucson to meet us, and to personally transport your adopted pet home, we may be willing to work with you. 

A home visit is usually required for the safety of our animals. We check the yard to make sure this girl cannot escape, no predator can get in, and also look for hazardous plants. 

We do not adopt our dogs out unless you have a secured, fenced yard, it’s a requirement for the safety of the dog. At the end of the application, please include the type of fencing and the height of the fence you have around your yard. 

If you're interested in Wiya or any of our dogs, please fill out a pre application at: http://www.azdesertrotti.com/html/to_adopt.htm
Once you have filled out the pre-adoption application, someone will contact you about the dog to answer your questions and tell you where our Sunday adoption event is held.

Our dogs are bathed, dewormed, vet checked, given their required shots, spayed or neutered, and microchipped. 

Our rescues are homed with foster parents. They are fostered in homes so that we can tell you a little bit about their personalities, feeding schedule, habits, behavior, whether they get along with other dogs. We can tell you if they are crate trained, if they are leash trained and house trained. Most dogs need a refresher course on potty training when they go to a new home. They need to learn your routine, and it will be up to you to teach them. 

Even the most abused animals can be wonderful pets. It takes patience, love and good food, along with fun and commitment to the animal. Fosters work with these animals. They are a part of our families, while we are lucky enough to have them.

animal.description:
Buddy Boy is a gorgeous. He is almosy 2 year old great pyrenese mix. He is playful and so fun to watch.   He loves chasing his tail and playing chase. He is so sweet and of course he enjoys belly rubs. Buddy is the perfect dog for a family and we hope to get him in a home with children.  If you are interested in adopting Buddy Boy,  please follow the link and complete an application.  

All our adoption fee of $150  includes spay/neuter, micro-chip, up-to-date vaccinations, including rabies. All of our pets are either tested heart-worm negative OR are currently being treated with the slow kill method approved by our veterinarian, on prevention & on flea/tick prevention.

In order to be considered for one of our beautiful pups, please go to our website and complete and application: https://mustluvdogs.org/adoption-application/
Please note that we are a DUE DILIGENCE adoption organization. Part of our approval process requires, among other things:
* Experienced pet home with verifiable vet references/history preferred, but we realize that everyone has to start somewhere, so all applications will be considered.
*The majority but not all of our pets require a fenced yard.
*Verifiable good veterinary history INCLUDING regular vaccination/visits and Good Heartworm Prevention history is a MUST!
*Adopter must be able to have time to spend with the pup and be able to provide the pup a safe environment to live.
*ALL our dogs are expected to be primarily INSIDE dogs.  They MUST sleep inside the home.  We truly understand that some folks have working dogs (i.e. farmers, ranchers,etc); however, the majority of our dogs have had a rough life prior to coming to us & we want to make sure that they are showered with LUV & maybe even a bit spoiled for the rest of their lives. 

Other facts are also considered, including whether children or other pets are a good fit with the dog. 

Must Luv Dogs reserves the right to deny any applications that we don't think are a good fit with the pup. Our first & foremost concern is the dog's best interest. It is our MISSION to place them in a home that is a great fit for their needs for a lifetime of luv & being part of a family.
*We will consider adoptions in any area; however, will do not ship or transport a puppy under the age of 12 mos. We will ONLY transport an adult dog on a transport approved by MLD, at adopter's expense.
* In order to be affordable and afford every family an opportunity to have a pup of their own, we keep our Adoption Fees at a low $150, but any additional donations are appreciated!

Please note that all of our pets are in private foster homes. In order to reduce any stress or confusion for our pups, we require a completed, approved application BEFORE setting up a meeting for any of fur-babies. Alternatively, you are always welcome to come meet any of our pups at one of our regular Adoption Events. They are always posted on PetFinder OR on our Facebook page: https://www.facebook.com/mustLUVdogs.org.

Finally, THANK YOU for considering Must Luv Dogs for your next pet. 

*Most dogs require a fenced area in yard. 
*Apartments okay IF nearby dog park or walking trails.
*ALL dogs must be INSIDE dogs. 
*We are a DUE DILIGENCE Adoption Rescue.  
*Must have good Vet history & Heart-worm prevention is a MUST!
*ALL dogs are fully vetted, spay/neutered and micro-chipped.

animal.description: Pugsley is a quiet and sweet little senior. He was found recently as a stray along with a female dog of about the same age and taken to a boarding kennel by a good samaritan. Pugsley has many fans (and is being networked by the kennel owner as well as FLA). He was recently diagnosed with Cushings Syndrome. Prior to the diagnosis, Pugsley was lethargic and just not feeling well overall. Once he began his medication, he found pep in his step and looks so comfortable. He loves when his human friends interact with him. He even lets them dress him in T-shirts. He really likes hanging out at FLA adoption events where he curls up next to any volunteer who sits down. "Finally, someone who will stay awhile," he seems to say. "Don't mind if I take a little nap here at your feet do you?" But as soon as his 16-month-old (human) buddy comes in to feed treats to all the dogs, Pugsley is all ears, eyes, and nose! He waits patiently though and takes his treats ever so gently from his little friend's fingers. Pugsley needs a home of his own with someone who would love a companion looking forward to his golden years who understands life's little pleasures of naps in the afternoon, dog treats, short walks, and plenty of pets behind the ear.

He’s a very laid back boy but will need time to adjust to a new situation. He would do best with an experienced owner that can provide calm, consistent guidance as he adjusts.  He is not playful with other dogs but would make a quiet, laid back companion for an older dog, He Does not do well with cats or small dogs.  Because he can be a bit nervous in new situations, we also feel he would do best in a home with no children. He loves car rides and long walks and also likes playing in water. He would do best in a home with consistent day-to-day activity. He does not do well with a lot of changes. He needs to have a fenced yard. He is housebroken and crate trained. Duke is neutered, HW checked and up to date on shots. For more information, please contact tamjov9@aol.com.

Visit our FAQ webpage for commonly asked questions about our adoption/foster process.

"A dark eyed beauty with a smile all her own."
Hi! I'm Ellie, a sweet, affectionate girl who is on a journey to find my forever home. I was rescued from an abandoned yard and am so excited to have an opportunity to find a family that I can love.
Training and trust have been key on the road to my transformation from orphan to loyal companion. I'm learning how to interact properly with dogs of various sizes, and how to listen to my handler when distractions exist. I know many commands, such as sit, stay, shake, no, come, go potty, down, roll over, and give kisses. I'm house trained, leash trained and crate trained.
I love as much positive attention as possible, (who doesn't?) and am not certain I want to share your affection with other animals. I like Nylabones, Kong toys and real bones but have a hard time sharing such treats with canine buddies. (I never got any before I was rescued.) A home where I can be the sole shining canine star would be ideal.
I've been described as very affectionate, (I love cuddles!), sensitive, and mostly submissive. I can be insecure when it comes to loud noises, such as thunderstorms and fireworks. My future owners will need to be patient and kind, and continue with my training and socialization.
I'm a sweet girl who is longing for a home where I'll never be left behind again. Can you help me complete my journey and make my dreams of a loving home come true?
For more information or questions, email Tim at tmb611@msn.com.
Click here to watch a video of Ellie.Last Day Dog Rescue now microchips all animals before adoption. Microchips are implanted between the animals shoulder blades and are a permanent form of identification. The microchips are registered to Last Day Dog Rescue with the adopter's info added once adopted. If the animal is ever lost and slips his/her collar/tags the microchip allows the finder to know who to contact if scanned for a microchip. Animals MUST still have a collar with tags on at all times. Per our contract, we take all our animals back if for any reason you can't keep your adopted animal.

Please understand the statements about this animal are based upon the foster home's evaluation of the animal. The animal might behave differently (negatively or positively) in your home. While the animal might be good with the current foster's dogs, cats, children, etc., it may not be with your animal(s) or children. The animal may be housebroken or litter trained in the home of the foster but may relapse in your home. The animal is represented to the public as it performs in the foster home and any statements made regarding the animal are conditional to that foster home setting. Please understand that statements made regarding this animal are simply overviews and are not guaranteed.

The Petfinder.com system requires that we choose a predominant breed or breed mix for our animals. Visual breed identification in animals is unreliable so for most of the animals we are only guessing at predominant breed or breed mix. We get to know each animal as an individual and will do our best to describe each of our animals based on personality, not by breed label.

Thank you for looking through our list of animals needing forever homes and choosing rescue first. We appreciate you stopping by.

Meet Keaton! He is a 5-6 year old mastiff mix looking for his forever home. Keaton is a big teddy bear, weighing in at 95 lbs, who loves to snuggle and thinks he is a lap dog. Keaton is dog reactive and prefers to be the only pet. He was found during the polar vortex in January 2019 by a good Samaritan, emaciated and in rough shape. She took him to safety and Hope Marie stepped in to provide the medical care, including eye surgery, to get him healthy and ready for his forever home. We don't think he has lived indoors much of his life and has separation anxiety when left alone. We are working on this with him as well as some other manners so he can be the best boy possible. Keaton would do best in a home that will be patient and will continue his training. While Keaton does very well with children, he is not aware of his size so a home without small children would be best for him.

Thank you for your interest in adopting from HMF. All of our pets are spayed/neutered, current on vaccinations, microchipped and otherwise healthy, unless noted in the description. Our adoption area is within 50 miles of Franklin/Bargersville, IN.

We hold a monthly adoption event on the last Saturday of each month from 12:00 noon until 3:00 p.m. at the new Center Grove Pet Valu store.
5885 N St Rd 135 Bargersville IN

Direct questions to: general@hopemariesfund.org

I am spayed, up-to-date on Rabies and yearly vaccines, heartworm negative and microchipped. I'm ready to go to a home who can with time, love, appreciation of my high energy level and patient experienced training will help me be all that I can and should be. Opt to Adopt! and give me a chance to love you! Copy/paste this link to your browser to fill out an adoption application for me at: www.ahimsarescuefoundation.org (under the adoption application button).

Characteristics: Sweet, playful, good with other dogs. Nonda is a bundle of joy. She's happy 24/7 and LOVES her human and canine mates. She loves to play fetch although she hasn't totally grasped the idea of bringing the toy right back to the thrower. Nonda is a very active dog and likes to play with anyone and everyone. She has never met a stranger. She is trained not to sleep on the bed but only because her foster mom doesn't have room for more babies! She would love to sleep at the foot of your bed. She is easy to train and learns quickly. Nonda loves water! She has her own swimming pool at her foster home. She doesn't chew on things she shouldn't and even if she happens to pick up the occasional flip flop, she doesn't damage it. She is used to a doggie door and has never had an accident in the house. She is not afraid of storms or loud noise. Nonda is simply a joy to have around. 

Ahimsa Rescue Foundation’s adoption donation varies between $150 and $250 for each pet. Ahimsa Rescue Foundation invests on average $200 per dog on medical, microchip and incidental care.

When you "Opt to Adopt" your ADOPTION PACKAGE INCLUDES:
-Pet that has been temperament tested
-Neuter/Spay
-Veterinary General Wellness Exam 
-Vaccinations: Rabies, DHPP, Bordetella
-Blood testing for heartworms, ehrlichiosis, lyme and  A Phagocytophilum disease  
-De-worming for hook, round, whip and tape worms
-Teeth Cleaning if needed 
-New ID Collar, slip leash and ID tags
-Microchip Placement and ID Tag
-Lifetime Registration of your Microchip with Avid microchip company.

There are many wonderful pets who find themselves homeless at no fault of their own.  Thank you considering a rescued companion from all our happy tails and everyone at Ahimsa Rescue Foundation! 

The first step of the adoption process is the on line adoption application at www.ahimsarescuefoundation.org  To be considered for the adoption of a pet you must submit the on line adoption application.  

We hope to see your application soon.
Ahimsa Rescue Foundation
www.ahimsarescuefoundation.org

animal.description:
**See more pictures of Mr. Big and his entire journey with us on his Facebook album**

https://www.facebook.com/pg/forgottendogsrescue/photos/?tab=album&album_id=2359870957365021

Are you looking for your one and only to walk off into the sunset with?  Well, Mr. Big is your guy!  After seven months in his foster home, he is ready to find his forever true love!  Are you his Carrie?
 
Mr. Big has quite the story.  We found him at the Yakima Humane Society in March 2019, where he had been picked up as a stray, and the second we met him, we knew he was leaving with us. While not 100% sure of his past, the scars on his body and the overall shape he was in when we got him into the rescue tells of a pretty tough history.  He came to us with many wounds from past dog fights, some of which were newer, others were much older.  He had entropion eyelids in both eyes, plus tears on the eyelids of both eyes.  His left eye was also ruptured. He hadn’t received care for this injury and he no longer had sight from that eye.  In addition, all four of his canines all of his top and bottom incisors were broken and the roots badly infected. All of these had to be removed, a total of 17 teeth. He was underweight, had some skin issues, a torn ACL, and had a large slit in his lower lip that was from a previous injury and hadn’t been fixed when it happened.  
 
Obviously, it took us quite a bit to get Big into better shape.  The wounds healed over time, we removed his ruptured left eye and repaired his eyelids, removed the necessary teeth and repaired his ACL.  Getting him into physical shape was only part of the journey we have been on with Mr. Big, however.  Given his unknown and, seemingly, difficult past we have taken some extra time to get to know him in terms of how he is with people and other dogs.  It was no surprise that he has some behaviors to work on and manage.  
 
To this end, he will need a special adopter and, given what he has been through, he deserves someone who will understand him and give him what he needs to stay happy, healthy and safe.  
 
Big’s age has been estimated between 8-10 years old.  And, in several ways he is definitely an old dude.  His favorite things are laying on the couch, napping and laying on the couch. ;)  Also, he likes to sniff and stroll around the yard and roll around a bit while he is out there.  Big, also, LOVES car rides. From the second he came to us, all Big wanted to do was go for a ride.  Seeing his face roll along on his first car ride out of the shelter was one of the best things to see ever. He just loves watching the world go by! 
 
Mr. Big is a big (80 pounds!) stubborn boy, and he is not a dog that automatically gives respect, you have to earn it.  Big learned to respect his foster mom within a couple of weeks due to her providing consistent boundaries and structure.  Once he learned to respect her, he got to get up on the couch for cuddles and all of the snuggles.  He will likely push some boundaries in a new home by invading personal space in inappropriate ways.  But, once his respect is earned, he is a wonderful gentleman!  
 
As with manners inside the house, Mr. Big is also learning appropriate leash manners outside the house. Much like in the home, Big will try to be the boss and want to charge ahead wherever he wants to go.  Again, he is stubborn!  After a bit of negotiation and setting clear boundaries he will walk (mostly) politely by your side.  He doesn’t need a lot of activity and after a 15-20 minute walk, he will want to go home and take a nap.  Or, lay on the couch.  
 
Due to his past and his observed reaction to other dogs outside of his foster home, Mr. Big needs a home with no other dogs or animals.

Mr. Big is crate trained and house trained.

His adoption fee is $350, and he is neutered, up to date with vaccinations, and microchipped. Are you interested in giving this special and deserving boy his forever home? Fill out an application from our website www.forgottendogsrescue.com.

animal.description:
This miracle young dog is Roxy, a pit bull less than a year old. Why is she a miracle you ask? Because it is a miracle she is alive and now thriving. Roxy was picked up by animal control with a chain collar embedded around her neck (before pictures can be provided upon request). The officers immediately rushed her to our vet where she underwent surgery to remove the collar. Weeks later, her stitches have been removed, the wounds completed healed and she has just a few small scars to show the ordeal she endured. You would think Roxy might hold a grudge against humans for what was done to her but she feels exactly the opposite. She loves people and wants nothing more than to be right where ever the people are-dogs really are the most forgiving of creatures. She loves children and is great with other dogs but we have learned she wants to play too roughly for cats. She really is a special dog and deserves a special home. Roxy is up to date with shots, spayed, crate trained, negative for heartworms and on prevention. If you think you can provide a loving home to Roxy, please visit our website at www.myhstc.org to submit an adoption application..

Adoption fee is $85 which includes all veterinary care

If you have never adopted from us before, we prescreen all applicants prior to meeting our pets. To be screened, please visit our website at www.myhstc.org to submit an application.

animal.description:
When we first rescued Marcus, (the day he was going to be euthanized) he had numerous puncture wounds believed to be from a pellet gun and/or dog bites, apparent chemical burns, cuts and tears, and malnourished at 20 lbs underweight. Yet even after all that, he is SO sweet to humans. 
    
We were asked to help Marcus because the folks at the shelter saw that this sweet guy did not deserve to be put down!! Now Marcus is in a foster home where he is able to be a normal dog, He is able to have frequent training and lots of love, attention, and exercise- which is what every happy dog needs! Marcus is about 4 years old, and now weighs about 55 lbs.

Marcus is extremely affectionate and eager to please people. He definitely will need to be in a home with a fenced in back yard. Marcus loves to be outside and roll in the grass, and he gets very excited about squeaky toys!  Marcus needs to be the only dog in the home.

If you are interested in meeting or adopting Marcus, email safepaws.florida@gmail.com.  Inquiries in Pinellas County please

Please note, we are not a shelter. We do not have a kennel or facility that you can visit and see all the dogs. Each dog is fostered in an individual home. We do rescue out of our private homes and in our spare time. So, you cannot come visit our dogs until you have gone through the application and interview process and we have contacted you about scheduling a visit.  We do not have set "hours" and we answer all calls and emails as quickly as we can.

animal.description: Must be within 1 hour drive of Essington, PA 19029, have another small dog or a dog friendly cat (Rylee loves cats), also a fenced yard is required ~ Cute Rylee was brought into a local high risk shelter after her last human passed away.  The shelter is a scary place for most but for a small pooch used to a home with a person that loved her, we can only imagine what went through her mind, which showed through her actions.  Rylee was acting out in the only way she knew how to protect herself, and that was trying to not allow people near her by being nippy & growly.  She didn't stand much of a chance getting adopted that way so PLDP pulled her into a foster home.  Trying not to let the same behavior start foster mom went super slow with her.  After a few days Rylee finally decided to come out of her crate with the help of her foster brother, and since has settled in her foster home. Because she has a few nips under her belt, we are recommending an adult only home.   Rylee gets along with most of the other dogs in the foster care but can be a little selective, but we believe she will be most happy with a fur-sibling so we are requiring another dog (about the same size as Rylee) in the house, or at least a playful cat so she has a buddy.  Rylee does enjoy playing with the friendly cats and kittens.  Rylee will sleep in her crate, on the sofa in in bed sometimes, foster mom tries not to let them get too spoiled in case rules are different in a forever home..  She is 100% PP pad trained, so not sure if she will ever get the hang of being housebroken.  Rylee likes to play chase with other pups, enjoys chewing on bully sticks, being brushed and seems to like being dressed up :) She hasn't had much leash experience.  Rylee is about 3YO, and she weighs about 8 pounds. If you think you are a good fit for our Rylee, please go to our website www.pldpaws.org and complete an application.  Rylee is spayed, chipped, UTD and heartworm neg.

animal.description:
Kobe is a two year old pit mix. He loves going for walks, playing with toys, going on car rides. He does have energy and needs structured exercise, but he can't go forever so if you're looking for a dog who can climb mountains with you, it's not Kobe.

He’s very friendly with the people he knows and trusts, but that list is short, and he is weary of strangers. He needs slow introductions to new people in order to warm up to them. Kobe will need an adopter that understands his need to take things slow, both with new people and new environments. 

Kobe is dog selective. He is not a dog who you should be taking to the dog park or anywhere where there is loose, unstructured play with random dogs, but he will definitely do well living with another dog or having dog friends that he is introduced too properly that is of a good temperament. He does not like dogs who are super in his face. He also does okay with cats, as long as the interactions are monitored.

Kobe is well trained, knows basic commands, walks well on leash, travels well in the car and has pretty good manners around the house. He loves his crate as well. 

His ideal home is a home with one or two adults only and possibly another well balanced dog. Kobe is a follower and he will pick up another dogs bad habits, as well as bounce energy off of them. For this reason, he should live with a dog who is secure and even keeled, not anxious or a dog with behavioral issues. Whoever adopts him should be comfortable handling him and advocating for his space when necessary. He needs someones lead to follow. Because of his low confidence and general distrust of the world, he can make poor decisions when left to is own devices. That's where structure, rules and guidance will come into play to help him navigate the world around him! He will have lifelong training support, but needs someone who is open to our guidance and can follow our instruction.

PLEASE DO NOT INQUIRE ABOUT KOBE IF:
-ANYONE under 18 lives in your home
-You have roommates
-You are against crates
-You are not open to balanced training

If you're interested in Kobe, email us at caredogvolunteers@gmail.com.


*PLEASE NOTE: All dogs are in foster care all over MA. They are NOT at the cat shelter, which is the address listed on Petfinder. There are ONLY cats there. We do not set up meet and greets with dogs until after you've been approved to adopt. Please do not email asking us if you can come by and meet a dog the same day.*

animal.description:
Meet Buster! Buster is spunky and looking for a forever home of his own as an only dog. Buster has decided blankets, beds, and laps are his favorite things in all the world. He craves human affection. He has received training from our behaviorist and is a smart boy that aims to please! He is strong so no young kids. He loves to get pets and snuggle and go for walks. He wants a fenced in yard to play in in his forever home.
We rescued Buster from Pasco County Animal Services in terrible shape. This poor boy is the product of severe neglect. The first time we met Buster, he was 100% without hair and covered in scabs. But, he was kind. He would wag his tail when you approached his kennel and stare right into your eyes.
Fast forward several months with devoted skin care and treatments from his foster family, Buster Brown is looking wayyyyyy better. We recently tested the remaining scabs/scarred areas with punch biopsies and learned that in those areas still without hair growth, it's quite possible that the severe case of dermatitis has made it impossible to clear fully or grow hair in certain spots.

What this means is, Buster will always retain some of the outward reminders of his horrible past. You will always be able to see a glimpse into the horror he suffered prior to joining the Maxx&Me family. What it also means is that Buster will always have a prominent and obvious testament to how far he has come. He beat death. He beat sickness. He beat the pain.
Buster is neutered, up to date on vaccines and microchipped. If you can be Buster's buddy please complete an adoption application at www.maxxandme.org! His adoption donation is only $225.
Maxx & Me is an all volunteer, all foster home rescue and do not have a shelter. Please allow at least 48 hours for applications to be processed (missing information may slow the process, so please take your time and be thoughtful in your answers). All dogs posted are available (so no need to ask). We place dogs based on best home for each dog and not order of applications received. Email us at maxxandmerescue@gmail.com for updates and questions. Thank you for choosing rescue.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Meet Apollo! A gorgeous 55-pound shepherd-lab mix born in 2016, Apollo was found on the harsh streets of Texas with a severe break to his front leg that required amputation, given the damage from being left untreated. Don't worry though, because Apollo has adjusted beautifully as a tripod! Despite the suffering he has endured, he remains sweet, loving and so very friendly to people and other dogs! Apollo is a couch potato but would thrive in a home with a fenced yard for his fun moments. Apollo can be a bit independent and may need some space until he gets comfortable. After that, be prepared to give belly rubs! He is a bit nervous around small children, and although he peacefully coexists with his foster cat sibling, he sometimes will engage the cat in a game of chase. He is housetrained, leash trained and neutered--no crate for this boy! A house with no stairs, or just a few carpeted stairs, would be best and Apollo needs short walks due to a torn ACL in another leg. Apollo's favorite things are
chew toys, belly rubs and kisses. He absolutely hates goats and flies!
If you would like to be the lucky one who gets to give this beautiful golden-eyed boy his happy ever after, please fill out an adoption application for Apollo here! Http://www.rescuedogsrocknyc.org

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
For those of you who do not know Wyatt... this boy is Special Needs. Please search
#WeareWyattsWarriors
to read about his journey.

Wyatt... This boy we affectionately call, Mr. Handsome is searching for his forever family. He is a lab/great dane mix that will be 5 years old in August. Unfortunately... he will need a very special family that will be able to attend to his daily care. He is paralyzed from the waste back. He has use of only one front leg. He is able to scoot himself around to his food, water or anywhere else he is determined to go. Watch it when you run the bathwater... he will end up in the bathroom too! He LOVES toys!! Here is his newest obsession... a little baby blankie with a lamb. He MUST have toys to keep him mentally stimulated and active. He is a happy boy that would love nothing more than you to lay with him and pet him from morning to night. You will have to be able to relieve his bladder and bowels as needed, every 4 hours and he does express urine and poo throughout the day. This all is no easy task as he is almost 100 lbs. We need your help to find the perfect home. He would do well with a cat or a dog but needs a calmer home than his current foster family. He gets frustrated when the other dogs go out to potty... he would love to go with them. Other than potty time... Wyatt is just like any other pup who likes to play, be petted, and snooze throughout the day. We want the BEST home ever for this handsome fella. Someone who will be able to give him lots of love and attention. He deserves a family to call his own. Applications are available on our website
www.onedogatatime.us
, if you feel you can accommodate Wyatt and his special needs.

Deitz is a 7 yr old American bulldog mix who is true to his breed. When he is not playing hard, he just wants to cuddle and warning... he thinks he is a lap dog. He enjoys chewing on bones, deer antlers, and playing with squeaky toys. A fenced yard would be ideal for his energy. If no fence, daily exercise would be a must for him. He rides great in the car and would be a great dog for hikes and long walks. At 7 years old, this boy still has lots of energy and love to share. He would do best in a calmer home without a lot of people in and out. He does good with medium to large dogs, small dogs we would not recommend. He is not good with cats. Older/considerate kids would be best for him to play with since he is a solid boy. He seems to do best with women and is slow to warm up to men, but once he trusts you, you're golden. He came to ODAAT after his human Mom passed away in their home. Deitz stayed by her side for days until they were found by family and sadly the family was unable to keep him. Understandably so, he will be protective of your family. He would never want to lose you. If you think Deitz would be a great addition to your family, please apply on our website at

www.onedogatatime.us

Thor has a white-and-brown short smooth coat, a long tail, and a gorgeous face with a large patch of brown around his right eye, a liver-colored nose, and short semi-erect ears.

Thor weighs approximately 60 lbs and is very strong on the other end of a leash. He wanted attention so badly when he was outdoors for his Petfinder/Facebook photos.

In compliance with the Ohio Revised Code, Sebastian (aka Thor) will be held for three days. He will be available for adoption on April 11, 2019 if he is not reclaimed.

animal.description:
PAW-sitively Adorable!
I am a smart, active girl who likes to jump, play,run, and WORK! Give me a job and I will perform it diligently. I have great focus and I know lots of tricks ..I would love to learn some more. I am nervous around new people and I am still learning some manners, but I love to go for long walks, car rides, or to sleep in the lounge chair with my human. I'd prefer a home with a huge yard and no other dogs or cats please.

Does Tina like other pets?

When I see other dogs out on a walk, I am not sure what to do! I bark at them, and I think I want to play, but then I'm unsure. I am going for some training to help me decide.

General socialization notes:

I needlots of attention and exercise!I am wary of new people and will bark at them. If they are quiet and don't pay attention to me, I get used to them. Men take a little longer to warm up to,unless they are quiet and calm. I respond well to treats and redirection. I can jump really high and if you leave food out on the counter, I just have to jump up and get it. .

Does Tina like children?

 I love olderchildren! I love to chase them and herd them, and I feel it is my duty to watch over them. I do jump up on them, so kids over 12would be best.

Favorite toys?

My favorite toy is a plastic milk jug. I tear up stuffed toys and squeakers in minutes. My foster Mom has found lots of good Kong toys for me to keep me busy.

Ideal forever home?

 I need a family who will be with me a lot and will keep my brain and body active. I need lots of room to run so a yard would be wonderful, and I would love to be your hiking partner! I would like a family who will play games with me and maybe take me for some fun classes so I don't get bored at home.

animal.description:
Sometimes this world just isn't fair and our sweet four legged friends find themselves without a home to call their own (through no fault of their own) and these two sweet girls are in definite need of a forever home. They are missing their mom who has passed away very recently and would love to find a couch to snuggle on again...please keep reading...

(Notes from their mom before she passed on...)

"Maddie is the black beauty with the soulful eyes. Robin is the little strawberry blonde sprite who never misses a thing.

They are litter mates, 6 and a half years old, spayed and housebroken.

My wish is to keep them together (although it is understood if that is something that may not happen). They are quite bonded though.

They love their soft couches, their toys and they watch TV---love love love TV!

They are extremely well mannered.

They are true people dogs. They go out for potty, sniff around a little and then want back in with their people for ear and belly rubs.

They are sweet, belly rub-loving babies who never expected to lose their momma."

PLEASE SHARE SHARE SHARE in hopes that someone that may see this story will open their hearts and homes to these ladies.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Stella Mae has been in Rescue now for over a year. Her foster mom says she is a wonderful girl that is ready for her forever home. Stella needs to be the only pet in the home and will not be a "dog park" kind of dog. Stella's ideal home would be with a family with an older child 10+ that would love to spend the afternoons throwing balls and playing tug-o-war together. Please submit your application today!

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Stella Mae- We were contacted by her family that loved her very much, but were working so much that she was left home alone and their neighbors could hear her crying. We did a courtesy post since we did not have any available fosters. Well, she was rehomed and shortly after that, she was found abandoned and very underweight near the airport in Pensacola. We immediately recognized her because she has the most Amazing ears - just check out her photos. So we took her in, got her back to good health and now Stella Mae is ready for her forever home. She is about one and a half years old and is a stunning, sweet fawn colored American Bulldog. She is very sweet and would thrive as an only pet home! We want to make sure that her next home is really her forever home. Please make sure you are planning to make a commitment to keep her in your family for the rest of her life before filling out our online adoption application. Amazing Grace Bully Rescue is a foster based rescue in the Pensacola, Florida area. We do not have a physical building. If you would like to meet any of our pups, the first step is to fill out our online application so we can contact you.

Our adoption fee for Stella Mae is $150 and includes her spay, current shots, rabies, and registered microchip.

If you would like to adopt this Amazing dog, please fill out our online adoption application at www.amazinggracebullyrescue.org

If you have any questions, feel free to text (best) or call and leave a message at (850) 723-2037.

animal.description:
Lola
Long haired chihuahua
About 2 years old
Female
Needs to be an only dog
Needs an adult home
Special needs - has focal seizures - well controlled with medication
Up to date with vaccines
Spayed
House trained
Crate trained
Walks well on a leash
Knows basic commands

Lola is a bit timid with new people, but once she gets to know you she is an incredible cuddle-bug :) She has focal seizures which are well controlled with medication. She would like a family with a quiet lifestyle - she does not do well with a lot of commotion or lots of people coming and going. She loves playtime in the yard, short walks, and is more than happy to cuddle up with you. She is a very sweet dog who had a terrible beginning in life, and we're committed to making sure that her future is way happier than her past!

To adopt please fill out the application at our website - https://www.furryfriendsct.org/adoption-application

ADOPTION POLICIES AND PROCEDURES:

Our goal is to help you find a wonderful new family member! We work closely with you to ensure that the dog you adopt will be a wonderful match for your family's make-up and lifestyle. Our adoption and foster placement processes includes an application, personal and vet reference checks, a home visit, and a meet and greet with the dog and all family members and other pets.

Placement is considered on the basis of the best interests of the dog and the best fit with the family - we do not adopt on a "first come, first served" basis.

We do not transport our dogs outside of the state of CT. If you live outside of CT and are able to travel to us after an application is approved, with your family and other pets, for a meet and greet and to complete the adoption in CT if that goes well, you're welcome to apply to adopt one of our dogs, as long as you live in one of the New England states. We do not adopt our dogs long-distance, or outside of the New England area.

PLEASE NOTE:  All of our dogs live in foster homes within the state of CT.  We do not have a facility.  For that reason we ask that you go through the application/approval process prior to a meet and greet, which is always part of our placement protocol.  We do this because we try to keep our foster families' day to day lives s uninterrupted as possible. You can fill out an adoption application at our website, at https://www.furryfriendsct.org/adoption-application .

Millie's heart broke when her owner passed away. She was only 6 years old and the family of her owner couldn't take her in. Millie has spent the last 2 years in boarding. It's really hard on her, as she's used to living in a home with all the comforts and love that come with that. animal.description:
Goldilocks is a petite 3-4 year old Lab mix. She is a human loving pup that came to us HW+ but has now been fully treated and is ready for her Forever home!  

Goldi needs to be an only pup, in an adult only household, but she makes up for it with how sweet, loyal and loving she is.  She is fully committed to keeping your yard free of squirrels, being your favorite hiking buddy and snuggling you hard at the end of the day.

While Goldi doesn't enjoy living with other dogs, she is ok hiking/walking around other dogs near as long as they don't get into her personal space.  

Goldilocks prefers females to males and would love to have a single female owner. She could do okay with a female/male couple if the male of the household is patient, calm and committed to helping to trust him slowly. She will need a calm, adult only household, no kids. She has a tendency to protect the woman of the house and get nervous.  

She would love a home with a fenced yard where she can run around or a family that likes to get outside regularly for activities. Because she can be nervous of some people/ males and dog reactive, we do not think she should live in a super populated area, downtown, etc.  

She is current on her vaccinations, spayed and micro-chipped.  Her adoption fee is $250.

animal.description:
My name is Roxy and I am yet another cute Great Pyrenees girl.  I am a considered a "smaller pyr" and should stay a "medium" sized dog based on Petfinder definition.  I was born in November 2018...plus or minus a month.  And yes, I am one of the "March Madness" Pyrs (the ones who came in from a less than desirable situation).

I have three siblings and all four of us were  nicknamed "the mohawk kids" since we all have cute hairdos.  I asked the lady who posts our photos on Petfinder to post one of my younger photos so you can see how cute I was with my toy.  

I am really shy and need some love and attention in a calmer household.  I'm okay with kids who are chilled out and my size and might enjoy a canine playmate, as long as he is a nice boy.  I do insist that we do a meet and greet, just to make sure.

As I've grown into my Pyr body, we've seen a few problems with my back legs.  It seems I have what is known as "luxating patella" or floating kneecap.  I've had one back leg operated on and am waiting to have the other one done.  best guess right now is that I won't be available for adoption until March 2021 at the earliest.

I'm hoping to find the perfect home soon so I know where I'll be living in 2021.  Won't you consider making me part of your family after my surgeries and recovery is done?

All Great Pyrenees require a fenced-in yard (at least four foot high). If you have questions about the breed or our adoption policies and procedures, please go to our website at www.agprescue.org. There's plenty of good information about the breed on our website - Pyrs aren't a breed for everyone! 

Our adoption application is online: http://agprescue.org/adoption-application/agpr-application-donations/

Please note that we are a small regional rescue organization. We will consider adopting to families within a four to five hour drive to Richmond, VA

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Prince Albert is a big young boy who needs a nice big yard or small acreage with secure fencing. He has no trouble climbing over our 5' tall fencing, but so far, our 6' fencing seems to keep him contained. He wants to be close to his people, and will definitely not stay in the pasture as a livestock guardian. BUT, he so far hasn't shown a lot of interest in living inside the house.

We think perhaps the ideal home for Albert would be a home in the country where he could enjoy life in a big back yard, preferably with another big dog as his companion. He doesn't bark excessively, so he shouldn't annoy your neighbors if he lives outside. Of course, he needs good shelter -- in his foster home, he prefers sleeping in the garage.

Albert is NOT safe with cats or chickens. He seems to be safe with goats, donkeys, and cattle, but since he lives in the yard and NOT the pasture, we can't say that is an absolute certainty. We will adopt him out only as a pet or guardian of hearth and home, NOT as an LGD.

If you would like to adopt Prince Albert, please complete an application on our website at www.bluebonnetrescue.org.

animal.description:
Polly is a lovely 10yr old girl that is soft hearted and gentle. On the verge of emaciation, she came into rescue in need of good food and a warm, sudsy bath. She introduced herself to us with a kiss, and has wagged her tail about 90% of the time. 

Polly loves other dogs and everyone she meets, but cats not so much. At the previous shelter she was so well behaved with other dogs that they deemed her a very special girl, and we certainly know why...she has a heart of gold! With small dogs, she likes them very much, but she gets excited when she first meets them. It would be best for them to meet and spend a little time together first if there's one in a potential forever home. 

One of our favorite things about Polly is her infectious smile and kind eyes. She has one of the best grins weve ever seen, and shes not afraid to flash it! Her entire face lights up! 

Another darling characteristic is that she sticks by your side in everything you do, always there just to let you know you have a friend supporting you. Quiet, well mannered and just happy to be with you, when you turn around you'll see her gentle eyes gazing at your with admiration.

Polly is on seizure medication and will be for the rest of her life. It's an inexpensive medication that has proven to work well for her. She will require regular bloodwork to monitor her levels (every 6mths). 

Polly does get slightly anxious when you leave, only displayed by barking and sometimes jumping on the door. She is non-destructive, however, and is very well mannered indoors. She is allowed to roam free in the house when nobody is home due to these good manners.

Polly must have had someone unkind to her, though, because shes afraid of little things like a brush, topical flea/tick prevention, veterinary work, or anything that you have in your hand that looks like its coming at her. She's made great progress but sometimes she still becomes afraid, so we work around it. Outside of those moments, however, she is affectionate, playful, gives hugs and is never afraid.

With a kind smile and gentle disposition, Polly is laid back and easy going. She does have some spunk though, for she loves a good walk and a car ride, and OH MY she loves a ball and a stuffed toy! She also loves waffle fries and a soft, cozy dog bed. The most adorable thing though is that whenever a new dog enters her foster home, shes thrilled! She always lets them know they are welcomed and that theyre going to have lots of love and lots of fun. Another one of Polly's favorite things to do is look out the window!

If youd like an established, kind soul that is deserving of a pampered life, yet loves to get out and go, youll want to meet Polly. If youre interested in doing so, just let us know!

Yo! My name is Rudy. I'm a small guy, loyal to the core, roughly 8-9 years old and I love to eat! I also love to cuddle, but I don't like being picked up. so just take a seat, let me jump up to you, and then I'll move in for the cuddles! 

I do well with other dogs, but since I still have a bit of spunk, I'll chase cats (FYI - the cats I currently live with tolerate my occasional chase). Small children make me nervous, so I'd prefer a home with adults only. 

In fact, let me be brutally honest with you. I'm a typical Chihuahua. I really need to be with someone who has owned Chihuahuas and understands me and my kind. Lucky Tales has also asked me to tell you that I'm much more fond of men than I am of women, so my ideal home would be one with no chicks, dames, gals, girlies - you get the idea. 

So, who is looking for a small, but devoted companion?! Anyone?

?I know it's a tall order to fill but my foster says the right person is out there for me, we just haven't found them yet, so I guess I'll just keep my paws crossed that it happens soon! Oh! I'm housebroken and crate trained, too. 

I'm up to date on shots, neutered, microchipped, and heartworm negative.

?My Adoption Fee is $100.00*

animal.description:
Roger is an 8-9 year old American Pit Bull Terrier who was previously adopted from Wish Bone and because his owner's circumstances changed, he needed to come back. He is searching for his forever home.

Roger is an active and playful dog, who enjoys both walks and car rides. He loves tug-of-war, but is missing a few teeth so it may take him a minute to get a good grip. He is especially fond of treats, and can be persuaded to sit and shake. Roger can be very vocal, sometimes "speaking" in the manner of Huskies, Beagles, and certain cats. His strong "Pit Bull accent" can be intimidating to visitors. Despite his gruff voice, Roger is very affectionate to humans, and guests should be warned before coming within kissing range. Towels are recommended.

While Roger's love of humans is exceptional even by dog standards, he has no tolerance for his own kind. Roger will need to be the only pet in his home, and special precautions must be taken in public. Dog parks, boarding kennels, and any off-leash situations will be unsafe for Roger, and continued training is strongly encouraged. 

Due to Roger's strong prey drive, his future home most not include cats, other dogs, or other small animals.

We likewise suggest a home with no children under the age of 12. Prior to adoption, approved applicants must dedicate time to working with Roger and getting to know him. He loves making new (human) friends, so apply today! Roger will be a FANTASTIC companion for the right person - the one who will understand him and love him unconditionally!

His minimum adoption fee is $195 plus a $12 fee, if 4 months or older, for rabies registration for McLean County residents. 

He has been neutered, microchipped, vaccinated, heartworm checked, dewormed, and is on flea and heartworm preventatives.

For information about this dog's breed(s), visit: http://www.dogbreedinfo.com/abc.htm 

To fill out our adoption application, go to: http://fs16.formsite.com/WishBoneCanineRescue/adoptionapplication/index.html

animal.description: This sweet girl and her sister landed in a shelter that does not allow the adoption of Pittie breeds. Unfortunately, they were heartworm positive and were treated in December 2019. DJ needs monthly HW preventative for the next 6 months and retested for HW to be sure she is clear...but that should not stand in the way of this very sweet and silly girl! DJ is used to living with her sister who is bossy! Her sister has been adopted and DJ is waiting for her turn. DJ would like a companion dog that is calm and easy going...people that like to snuggle...and a comfy place to hang out. If you are interested in DJ, please fill out the online application at www.etnpitbullrescue.org or email us at etnpitbullrescue@gmail.comEast TN Pit Bull Rescue adopts out to companion homes only. Adoptions require an application that is verified, a meeting that includes ALL members of the household, a home visit, and a trial period. We do not place our dogs in homes with unaltered pets or homes that have pets but do not have a vet. All of our dogs are placed as inside pets, spayed/neutered, micro chipped, vaccinations current, and HW- or treated within the last 6 months for heart worms by our vet. Adoption fees start at $150 for adults and $200 for pups. If you are interested in offering this pet a responsible and loving home, please fill out the on-line application at www.etnpitbullrescue.org. East TN Pit Bull Rescue is a Tennessee Non-profit corporation with 501(c)(3) status. Your donations to sponsor pets are tax deductible. If you would like to sponsor this pet, please go to www.paypal.com and make a donation to donations@etnpitbullrescue.org OR contact Butler's Animal Clinic at 865-531-7311 to make a donation on the East TN Pit Bull Rescue Account. Please be sure to add the pets name in the comments section. Your donations are greatly needed and appreciated.

animal.description:
Meet Opal!
Opal has a heartbreaking rescue story. This beautiful pittie and dalmation mix was found on in the middle of the road unable to move. She was in such bad shape that the good samaritan that found her thought she was literally a bag of trash. She was not trash, she was a puppy. She had suffered in ways we can’t imagine. 

Opal is a true testament to resiliency, prayer, love and life! She has made a full recovery and life has never been better for Miss Opal, you can see it in her eyes! (Not to mention how strikingly beautiful those bi-color eyes are!). 

Opal absolutely LOVES people. She is so kind, loving and playful. Opal is very smart, knows her commands and will indicate when she has to go potty. She LOVES dogs and has been in a foster home with multiple fur siblings. This is the type of environment we wish for Opal as she continues to thrive.

Opal loves to exercise, she loves tennis balls, loves to swim and loves her foster mamma! A fenced yard will be required to adopt Opal, and Opal wants me to tell you that a pool is a big plus ;)

If you are interested in adopting this beauty queen, please apply at www.twotailzrescue.org!
