animal.description:
Figuro is a staff favorite-- he is a very affectionate, good-natured boy.  This gem has been overlooked so far because he doesn't "stand out" physically, and is just a quiet, mellow guy - but his lucky adopter will be glad that others passed up such a fantastic dog!

Fig has some allergies which are managed by two medications and is currently on a prescription limited ingredient diet (Science Diet D/D) ; without medication this boy becomes terribly itchy and loses his fur, so it's important that his adopter is prepared to continue his daily meds for life! He is also receiving medicated baths and spray several times a week.

A note from one of our dog volunteers/ #1 fan - " Figuro is just my idea of perfection. He looks at you with these sweet sweet eyes. He has such a gentleness about him. And the way he checks in with you when on walks... oh, melt my heart, little buddy! "

Figuro wants to be the only dog in his home. He was recently returned and the family that adopted him loved him but weren't able to successfully integrate him with their other dogs. He is fine with passing dogs and dogs in the neighborhood, but should be the only dog in his forever home.

He has tested well with cats here at the shelter, but would have to be slowly introduced to a cat in his new home, and we are not sure if he would guard food or toys from a cat like he has previously done with dogs in his prior home.

Come meet him today!

___________

All adoptions are by appointment only. Please find the animal you like in the Adoptable Pets area of our internal website and then submit a questionnaire to our adoptions team at adoptmcasac@montgomerycountymd.gov Full COVID-19 adoption procedures can be found here: https://www.montgomerycountymd.gov/animalservices/adoption/covidadoption.html Website: montgomerycountyMD.gov/animalservices 

___________ 

**** PLEASE NOTE: Our adoption process can move quite quickly, and applications are considered on a first-come, first-served basis. Some animals, especially puppies/kittens and small dogs, can go very quickly. For this reason, we recommend that if you see an animal you are interested in, you send in an adoption questionnaire as soon as possible. Please do not bring your current pets to the shelter. If you intend to adopt a dog and want the new dog and your current dog to meet, that can be scheduled with the help of your Adoption Counselor. Thank you! ***** Montgomery County residents are required by law to purchase a Montgomery County Pet License for all dogs and cats at the time of adoption. Pet licenses are $12 annually for animals over 1 year and free for animals under 1 year.

animal.description:
•Min Pin, •male, •6 years, •17 lbs.

NO CHILDREN 
MUST HAVE A PHYSICAL FENCED YARD

Pirate is a very endearing dog. Just do not call him cute, he has the spirit of a Doberman packed into a Min Pin body and wants you to respect his authority. His life work is to keep his home safe. Pirate loves to let you know when someone rings the doorbell, even if the doorbell is on the TV, and even if he is not always the first dog to notice, he is always the most enthusiastic. 
Pirate enjoys quick patrols of the yard to see what has changed, and do some sniffing, then it is back in the house to see if the food dishes got magically refilled while he was out, and then do some serious napping. 
Pirate loves a routine, and he loves his bed. He will sometimes join you on the couch and nestle near you. He is not a big snuggler but he does like gentle scratches on his chin and ear rubs, as long as he is in the mood. At night he prefers sleeping on the couch and keeping the house safe while you sleep. 

Pirate is a unique dog with some unique behaviors. He had a stroke when he was younger which left him with some ataxia and vision differences, along with sensory issues, and some anxiety. Touch can be overwhelming, new surfaces take some figuring out, and a lot of sound or activity will really overwhelm him. He does not like being jostled or bumped into, and being picked up is too much for him, we do not suggest it. This means you have to make some accommodations, like transporting him in his carrier, and letting him decide when it is time for affection. 

Pirate cannot do stairs but can navigate ramps and can jump on the couch like a pro as long as he has solid footing. Pirate does not do well on walks because you can never be sure when he will be overloaded by his environment, so a fenced yard is necessary. 

Pirate can handle a quiet visitor or two, as long as they respect his rules and boundaries, and he will quickly made friends with people who know that you should ask before you pet, especially if you bring treats.

Pirate is house trained but he tends to go on a schedule, and if he needs to go he needs to go. He does his best to use the pee pad if no one is around to let him out but no one is perfect. 

Pirate lives with other dogs and cats, and is always polite but not looking to play or really interact with them. He likes to be left out of their games, although he is a champion at the Kong Wobbler.

**********************
Due to Massachusetts State Regulations we are unable to adopt to residents of Massachusetts at this time. We apologize for any inconvenience.
********************

** If you are interested in adopting this dog, you must first complete an adoption application a thttps://www.shelterluv.com/matchme/adopt/PEP/Dog. Or visit our site (http://peppertree.org/adoptlist.php) and learn about other Peppertree dogs. *Note: visual breed identification in dogs is unreliable so for most of the dogs we are only guessing at predominant breed or breed mix. We get to know each dog as an individual and will do our best to describe each of our dogs based on personality, not by breed label.

George is around 4. He generally likes other dogs but does need proper introductions to them and is not a "dog park dog." He needs slow intros to new people to be set up for success, this means that anyone who is new to George will have to be okay with taking it slow. But once he trusts you, he’s very sweet and snuggly. No kids for George. He likes to run, walk, hike, swim and is an all around great adventure buddy. He would do best with a fenced in yard and it is a requirement to adopt him; the more time he spends outside, the happier he is. He knows his basic commands and walks well on leash!

-ANYONE under 18 lives in your home
-You have roommates
-You are against crates
-You are not open to balanced training
-You do not have a fenced in yard

animal.description:
Gertie is a young piebald dachshund mix and weighs about 12 pounds.  We rescued Gertie from a shelter where it seems that she had given birth sometime in the recent past, although she did not have any puppies with her.  She was very sad and wanted out of the shelter, we can’t blame her.  At first, Gertie thought she needed to be defensive with other dogs, we think she was accustomed to protecting herself in her past life, since she wasn’t spayed, it’s possible all of the boys were after her.  After a few days Gertie settled in and seemed less fearful around new dogs.  When meeting new dogs in new situations she can be standoff-ish, but once she sees a dog is not a threat, she’s all about making friends and wags her tail.

Gertie has been living in foster care with 2 medium dogs and is doing great.  She can sometimes be jealous as she thinks she should get the number one spot in the line for attention, she’s probably never had attention before and she’s really soaking it up now. Gertie LOVES taking car rides and sits calmly and is quiet. She loves toys now and loves playing with her foster friends outside on nice days. She has a very silly side that we love and makes us laugh.  While her foster mom is at work, Gertie stays in a crate.  She does fine in the crate but is excited for freedom in the evenings.

I am 13 weeks old, and love people!

Adoption Donation $450

My litter includes Tulip, Posie, Carnation, Cricket, Dafodil, and Tigerlily!

All dogs are microchipped, neutered/spayed, current on all vaccines, heartworm tested and started on Tri Heart Plus & Vectra 3D.

I will be available for adoption on April 6th. I cannot have any visitors before April 6th. You will need to fill out an online application and receive a phone call back from a staff member that everything is ok with the application prior April 6th. All family members and any dogs from the household need to be present at the time of the adoption. 

We open at 9 am Saturday mornings and we will be helping adoptions in the order of when they submitted an approved application to us. There will be a sign in sheet on the front door at 8:30 am so that we can pull applications for the people that arrive between 8:30-9 am. Again, the order in which adoptions will come in to the shelter to see any adoptable dogs or cats first thing on Saturday mornings will be as to when the application was submitted to Animal House Shelter so there is no need to come to the shelter any earlier than 8:30 to sign in. This will be the procedure for people that arrive between 8:30-9 am.

After 9 am, on Saturday mornings it will be first come, first serve after we help all of the adoptions that signed in between 8:30-9 am. Most people submit general applications to us which do not specify a name or a particular litter they are interested in so there is no way for us to know until people arrive Saturday morning at 8:30 how many people are interested in a particular litter, puppy, kitten, cat or adult dog. We always have around 300 dogs & cats available for adoption and the adoption counselors will help you to find the right companion for your family!

Please fill out an online application and we will give you a call as soon as we receive it. Visit our ‘Adopt’ page to view adoption process steps, policies, requirements and FAQ. View our ‘Visit’ page for hours and directions to our shelter. We look forward to seeing you soon!

Link to the Adoption Application: https://www.animalhouseshelter.com/adopt/adoption-aplication/

Our website is always kept 100% up to date with who is currently available. All new animals (40/week) are added to the site 2 weeks before their availability date to give you time to fill out your adoption application and get the family ready to come out to the shelter that day. As soon as animals are adopted, they are moved to the Adopted Pets page so if they are still listed on the Adoptable Dogs or Cats page, they are still available. Keep any eye on our website for any animals being added as available for adoption as new animals are added everyday! We would recommend if you haven’t done so already that you submit a general online adoption application with us so it is on file for when you are ready to come out and adopt.  The adoption counselors will be able to show you many that would be a good fit for your family.  We do go in order of when you submitted your application with us.  So it is always best that you get your general application for any animal in with us as soon as possible.

I'm GIMLI!  I was turned into the shelter by a kind man who found me huddled in the hay in his barn after he tried to find my owners. I need at least one other dog in my new home and a family that is committed to helping me become the spectacular dog I know I can be.

animal.description:
I'm little Noel!  I'm the happiest, busiest little girl you'll meet.  I've had a lot of experiences since I was born on January 4, 2019.  My story is below.

----

Little Noel’s had a pretty eventful life for being only 8 months old!  Noel has IMHA – immune mediated hemologic anemia. This means her body’s immune system is destroying her red blood cells and platelets.  We’re not sure how this occurred. Her sisters, Snickers (now “Cedar”) and KitKat (now “Mayce”) are fine.

The job of red blood cells in the body is to carry oxygen. When red cells are decreased, less oxygen is available to the cells of the body and the dog becomes weak, has labored breathing, darkened urine, bruises easily and can bleed into vital organs such as the brain or spinal cord. Causes of the condition are varied and include: vaccinations, antibiotics, cancer, genetic factors, bacterial/viral infections, toxins, and radiation. But in most cases no obvious factor is determined.

Fortunately on May 27 Noel’s foster mom, Marie, noticed that her gums were very white. We called on Dr. Kay who met us immediately and told us to get her into emergency care. Yes… on Memorial Day. We took her to Blue Pearl Veterinary Hospital where she was seen by Dr. Campbell who diagnosed her condition, gave her a transfusion and kept her overnight. We weren’t sure she was going to live through the night. A bone marrow aspirate indicated that she wasn’t producing any new red blood cells at all. 

Gradually Noel’s red blood cell counts started to improve and she became a boisterous, romping puppy again. Blood draws were only done once a month as we very slowly decreased her azathioprine and prednisone, added plavex to her regimen and her red blood cells started to function at almost normal levels.

Noel is at Casa UPP tormenting the adult dogs. Fortunately the older dogs will play and run with her in the yard. Noel is ball obsessed. And she wants you (i.e., “me”) to spend my life throwing it for her to retrieve. I try and toss it in varied directions to keep her on the hunt as long as possible but she’s insatiable and will search for the darn thing until she finds (and returns) it. She loves tossing it in “difficult to recover” places – the pool, the window well, the water bucket, the kitchen sink and the toilet (if I’m not quick at closing the lid). The latter is my least favorite.

Noel's complete story is posted on our facebook page:  https://www.facebook.com/pg/UtahsPerfectPointers/photos/?tab=album&album_id=2660291533989169&__xts__%5B0%5D=68.ARCzsdYCf0k-V0bHh_1kmIjVTIfYRHiXnfZ3fME9TmuKcrCPuw9sd49-2-q2CSjI98D_U6-gQTdi0RBkp1lIBLxbPV2PfL3Zk9FgwjGQzPTK9CM-dNkgkc2p3nYNln4UjnkAVKFtvYFYPf_EWbm590PF72WokCnEu3CZOWvyPDCofgn9WNGdQFJRwQ2y-5JSylhm0EpBFcNMOBGAKg4TkLDSC3h4B7bXfthxq1sYLC-RUkPgh9VhEfzu89OOvVakp9fwkqun9myVcAU9xJqxP9xFFWR5veVn4ytN3JEFkCU2G_ds-q4f6oUJ3IBKVONfHMH_hS7K_bz0lhDvv3xg7SZ4mMQ6BL3V6knEAb__OTLUFKfSq1crG9GGO-mtyNZy-BTKbaXHwLuzQS-5Vg1TDwpaLkpRyPegICwdzh9kyhe8zos8TsU2VcO19f05BjibpQgj9-8VyP3FzTL8TK6H&__tn__=-UC-R

In order to apply for adoption of Bentley-Craig, you must fulfill these requirements:

ADOPTION REQUIREMENTS
- Must have experience with Terrier breeds.
- Must have experience with behavior issue & dominant history dogs.
- Must commit to work with a private dog trainer in the home.

Bentley is currently living in foster. Here's what his foster dad has this to say:
For the most part, Bentley is house trained. He's had some accidents but he will bark, howl and paw at you when he needs to go out. He loves his walks and does good in the car. He doesn't bark except when he needs to go out. He doesn't beg for food and hasn't torn up anything in the house. Bentley does not need to be crated, but he is fine in his crate. Essentially, Bentley sleeps, goes for walks, sits in his foster dad's lap and plays with his Kong. He has guarding issues, so no stuffed animals or balls. He does not guard his Kong or other toys that have treats associated with them.

Because of his guarding issues, Bentley needs a home with no children and an experienced owner committed to training and working with him. He originally came to us from California so much of his background is unknown.

Please contact our shelter to learn more at 410.268.4388.

animal.description:
Well, mama always said there's a lid for every pot, and I'm sure hopin' she was right!  The truth is I'm not perfect! I have a few flaws...and I'm comin' to you hat in hand, hopin' and prayin' that you can see your way to lovin' me despite my quirks and imperfections. To be honest (and I promised I would be!) I don't like men. I don't like cats (except to chase!) and if that's not enough, I'm a barker...yup! there it is out in the open! No guys, no cats, no condos, no apartments.  And I need slow intros to other dogs, so I guess I better say no dog parks. 
Phew! I feel better with that out in the open. Now on the plus side, I'm funny, quirky, and once I get to know you (and assuming you're the right gender!) I am as sweet and loving as a girl could be, you'll be watchin' tv and my head will be snuggled right up on your lap. And not to boast but I've done great things with my training! I walk really well on a leash, I heel politely and I park my bum down as soon as you say Sit! My training has helped me with new situations that previously scared me, so I've made great progress. I love all kids, including boys!
My trainer will consult with you to ensure that I'm the right fit for your family.

Name: Coffee
Weight: 30 lbs.
Age: 2.75 years
Gender: female 
Breed: lab mix 
Colour: black 

Good with adults: Good with women, not good with men
Good with kids: yes, loves kids
Good with other dogs: no
Good with cats: absolutely no cats
House trained: yes
Crate trained: yes, goes in when told
Energy level: medium 
Can be handled/touched: yes 
Barker: Yes - no condos or apartments
Flight Risk: she will walk in between your legs and will go out the door with you.  Better to be safe and keep a eye on her with open doors.   
Food aggressive: no 
Walks on a leash: yes, has been in training and has her basic obedience down. 
Rides well in a car:  yes 
Destructive: no
Needs a home with a yard: daily walks and potty breaks will be ok 
Needs a home with another dog: no, she should be the only dog
Can live in an apartment environment: no
. 
Foster update:
Coffee is one of a kind. She is loyal, a great snuggler, always by your side, and smart! Her idea of a perfect night? Cuddled up on the couch, head on your lap. She is crate trained (will go in for treats- but much prefers to be with you!) She is not food aggressive, and can be easily trained with treats! Coffee's previous history is unknown and she is wary of everyone she meets, especially men, but once she warms up to you- she will be your best friend. Once she knows you're her forever mama, she will be extremely loyal to you and only you!  
She needs slow introductions to other dogs but has been fine in her foster home with other dogs around. Coffee has been in a training program and now has her basics down. She walks well on a leash, heels politely and knows how to sit. Coffee loves snuggles but does need slow introductions to new people. With her training that she has done, she is doing much better with new situations that were previously scary to her. Coffee comes with a trainer consult for potential applicants to ensure she is the right fit for your family. 

PLEASE READ ALL THE INFORMATION IN THE DOG'S PROFILE, AS WELL AS THE INFORMATION ON OUR WEBSITE, niagaradogrescue.com , BEFORE EMAILING US WITH QUESTIONS. OUR VOLUNTEERS USE UP VALUABLE TIME ANSWERING QUESTIONS WHERE THE ANSWERS ARE READILY AVAILABLE ON THE WEBSITE. 
SINCE WE ARE ENTIRELY VOLUNTEER RUN AND RECEIVE A HIGH VOLUME OF APPLICATIONS, IT MAY TAKE AT LEAST 2-3 WEEKS BEFORE AN ADOPTION TEAM MEMBER CAN RESPOND TO YOUR APPLICATION. PLEASE BE PATIENT. 
WE ARE FOSTER BASED, THEREFORE WE DO NOT HAVE A FACILITY.  MEET & GREETS FOR DOGS IN CANADA WILL NOT BE ARRANGED UNTIL AN ADOPTION APPLICATION IS APPROVED. THANK YOU!!!	
Please visit our website @ https://www.niagaradogrescue.com/ or apply for adoption @ https://niagaradogrescue.com/adoption/.    If the dog is not listed on the NDR website, please put the dog's name down anyway, profile just may have not been uploaded yet

Animal Rescue Recon makes sure that each dog is current on its vaccinations, has been or will be spayed or neutered, and is microchipped to help keep pets out of the shelters and get them back home where they belong. For more information or to schedule an appointment contact Animal Rescue Recon (925) 392-7654

-----
Please tell us a bit about yourself/family
•  What city do you live in?
•  Do you rent or own?
•  Any children in the home?  What ages? List all family members living in home
•  What is your work schedule?  Family schedule?

•  Provide detailed pictures or video of your fenced yard - entire perimeter including gates and the bottom of the fencing.  Yard must be free of foxtails and fully secured.

Most of our available dogs can be seen at Pet Food Express in Antioch on Saturdays from 10 AM to 1 PM

Our adoption fee is $300 for Dogs and $350 for puppies (under 6 months). The fee covers the cost of having the dog fully vaccinated, spayed/neutered, and microchipped.

animal.description:
ECHO is a handsome, energetic, 4-year-old Border Collie mix with an excellent resume!

He's a hard worker, or at least he would be if he had a job to do!  Border Collie's are working dogs and ECHO is a quintessential Border.  He wants a job!  He's always looking for something productive to do so he would be happiest as part of a family who keeps a small flock of pet sheep in their backyard.  Failing that, he would really like to be with a person or family who enjoys an active lifestyle.

If you are into camping, hiking, playing frisbee, running or perhaps interested or involved in canine agility games and competitions, ECHO is your man!

ECHO is very clever, most Borders are, so he needs mental stimulation as well as physical challenges. The more enrichments you can provide the happier he'll be.

They only flaw he's got, and it's not a big one, is that he doesn't like to share his food.  He's protective of his bowl when he's eating.  So he should be fed separately from other dogs and just allowed to eat his meal, undisturbed.  This behavior can either be accommodated as described, or addressed with training.

ABOUT THE BORDER COLLIE

Affectionate, Smart, Energetic

Borders are athletic, medium-sized herders standing 18 to 22 inches at the shoulder. The overall look is that of a muscular but nimble worker unspoiled by passing fads. Both the rough coat and the smooth coat come in a variety of colors and patterns.

The almond eyes are the focus of an intelligent expression—an intense gaze, the Border’s famous “herding eye”, is a breed hallmark. On the move, Borders are among the canine kingdom’s most agile, balanced, and durable citizens.

The intelligence, athleticism, and trainability of Borders have a perfect outlet in agility training. Having a job to perform, like agility—or herding or obedience work—is key to Border happiness. Amiable among friends, they may be reserved with strangers.

WHAT'S NEXT?

Well, you can foster, foster-to-adopt, (in case you're not sure) or adopt ECHO.

To get the ball rolling, just fill out our online FOSTER/ADOPTION APPLICATION, which can be found in the main menu of our website or at the bottom of this page - simply copy and paste the link into your browser. EASY PEASY!

Once we've reviewed your application, arrangements can be made for you guys to meet! It'll be kind of like a blind date!

***

This pet is spayed or neutered in accordance with our strict policy wherein all animals are altered prior to adoption.  This pet is dewormed, current on vaccines, and started on monthly flea/tick and preventatives. 

Animal Alliance's policy is that we will adopt dogs younger than 1 year old to families with children under 9 years old. We do not adopt dogs 1 year or older to families with children under 9 years old due to the unknown history of adult dogs. 

Prior to submitting an application, please see the Animal Alliance Adoption Process for adoption details. 

To fill out an adoption application, go to:
https://www.animalalliancenj.org/fosteradoption-application/

animal.description:
Friends to the Forlorn
Adopt-a-BullBreed: Pit Bull Gender: Female Estimated Date of Birth: February 28, 2016 Size: 45 lbs Location: Dallas, GA
RESCUING RUBIA
Rubia came into Fulton County as a very pregnant stray. She gave birth the very next day to 10 puppies and to make matters worse, she was extremely protective of the pups. Unfortunately, between Rubia's terrible condition, the lack of milk production, and the shelter environment, 8 of the 10 pups passed away. Rubia then lashed out and bit a kennel worker that was cleaning her run. Rubia and her 2 remaining pups were extremely sick and we were lucky enough to have a foster step up for their tiny family. After being seen by our vet, we had to pull the surviving pups from Rubia in order to bottle feed them as there was no way they would have survived if we didn't. Rubia has an advanced case of heartworm disease and her chest was filled with fluid. It will be a long road to recovery for Rubia and her babies. Sadly, neither of Rubia's two remaining pups pulled through.
ABOUT RUBIA
Rubia is happy to be out of the county shelter and is still a little skeptical of new people, but she is not lashing out at anyone. Now that she is away from her pups and she is having good human experiences, Rubia is actually quite happy and accepting of new people. She is full of tail wags and love. The fluid swelling up in her chest has gone down completely and Rubia's true personality is coming out even more. Rubia is cautious with strangers, but quickly learns to trust. She is in heart failure, but her heartworms have been treated and she is doing extremely well. Dogs can lives for years with bad hearts and she's on medication to help. Rubia is crate trained and housebroken (she's never had an accident). She's a happy girl and is very loving and grateful to be out of the pound. She's an expert at dramatically throwing herself on the floor for belly rubs! She appears to be good with other dogs and kisses the dogs through their crates. Rubia needs a foster or an adopter to complete her rescue journey.
Photo Album of Rubia: https://www.facebook.com/pg/FriendsToTheForlornPitbullRescue/photos/?tab=album&album_id=2694788110579338
Our adoption fee is $300. All dogs are current on vaccinations, spayed or neutered, micro-chipped, on heartworm prevention, and are fed top of the line grain-free food.www.savingpitbulls.org

animal.description:
Piccolo is a project dog.

PICCOLO is a 1-2 year old terrier mix. He has a vivid white and black coat and weighs 14 pounds. PICCOLO is a little particular with other dogs and can be bossy, so he might do best alone :)  

Project dogs are very scared of strangers.  These dogs will not go to strangers, they will run into a corner or under something to get away.  They know us and we can pick all of them up, but we do not know if they will bite a stranger.  Some will just run away.  Most of them are our older dogs.  Although, we do have some younger ones.  The older dogs are also in need of a dental and rabies.  These dogs have been with us from 6-10 years now. These dogs do not leave our fenced area.  Nothing goes in and nothing goes out.  They are welcome to live their lives out with us where they are comfortable.  However, I think that some could learn to live in a home.  They need time and patience.

If you are serious about adopting one of these dog(s) you must be willing to commit to visiting every day for approximately 2 weeks.  We have done this with several of our dog(s) and it works.  When they go to your home they are familiar with you.  In a matter or several days or even hours they trust and feel safe with you.
  
If you cannot commit to the time needed please do not waste your time or mine.  This is the only way you can adopt a project dog.

If you would like to meet one of the project dog(s), please go to our website, kritterkamprescue.com and fill out the adoption application. It only takes a few minutes to do. Then, if approved, you may call or email for an appointment.  This is usually all very quick and easy. However, if you have any difficulty or don't receive a reply within 24 hours, please call us @ 916-691-1364.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Personality:
Ziva came to us from a hoarding case in TN and is adjusting to being in a loving home and learning what love and affection are. She is settling in well but will need continued love and guidance in her adoptive home. More information will come as Ziva settles into her foster home.

None of our foster dogs are tested with cats because we have no way of testing them with cats. Siberians are notorious for their high prey drive and typically kill cats, rabbits, chickens, birds, squirrels, opossums, etc., so we we don't have much success adopting them out to homes with cats. Most of our foster dogs are with us for killing cats, chickens and goats to begin with so our assumption is they are not good with cats and other small things that move.

Siberians are typically good with children of all ages and the only reason we would not list them as not good with kids is because they may be too energetic and bouncy and knock over a toddler.

Southern Siberian Rescue is a volunteer based 501(c)3 organization based out of Raleigh, NC, so we do not have a physical facility with operating hours that you can visit to meet our dogs. All of our foster dogs are in our personal homes. You need to fill out our adoption application (http://www.southernsiberian.com/info/adoption) and get approved to adopt and then we will set a time for you to meet our foster dogs. As a volunteer based group, we all have jobs, family, personal dogs and other commitments but we try to acknowledge and process applications as quickly as we can. That being said, we try to keep our available foster dogs as current as we can also but it is time consuming to get pics and information on new dogs so not all of our dogs are listed at all times. Please fill out our application and then we can discuss dogs that will work for you and your situation. We average 40-45 Siberians in our program so we are certain we have one that will work for you. Please know that we are not obligated to answer inquiries on dogs as we will focus on approved applicants. Again, there is ample time to discuss all of our foster dogs AFTER we have an approved application on file. We do adopt out of state as long as we can get a home check done. We ask that you, your family and existing pets make the trip to NC to meet and adopt our foster dogs.

SSR can not and will not hold dogs for anyone. If we do, that means another Siberian will die in a shelter because a shelter dogs time is very limited, as is our foster space. We do our best to process applications in the order received and first application gets first interest in our foster dog(s). We understand that there will be scheduling conflicts with home checks and meet and greets but we will try to accommodate for that if a potential adopter has interest in a particular foster dog in our program.

All Southern Siberian Rescue foster dogs are microchipped, up to date on shots, spay/neutered, on monthly heartworm preventative and flea and tick preventative. For additional information on Southern Siberian Rescue and Siberian Huskies, please visit www.SouthernSiberian.com. To fill out an application, please visit

http://www.southernsiberian.com/info/adoption
.

All our adoption fees include spay/neuter, micro-chip, up-to-date vaccinations, including rabies. All of our pets have either tested heart worm negative OR are currently being treated with the slow kill method approved by our veterinarian, on prevention & on flea/tick prevention.

In order to be considered for one of our beautiful pups, please go to our website and complete and application: https://www.mustluvdogs.org/adoptable-pets.
Please note that we are a DUE DILIGENCE adoption organization. Part of our approval process requires, among other things:
* Experienced pet home with verifiable vet references/history preferred, but we realize that everyone has to start somewhere, so all applications will be considered.
*The majority but not all of our pets require a fenced yard.
*Verifiable good veterinary history INCLUDING regular vaccination/visits and Good Heartworm Prevention history is a MUST!
*Adopter must be able to have time to spend with the pup and be able to provide the pup a safe environment to live.
*ALL our dogs are expected to be primarily INSIDE dogs.  They MUST sleep inside the home.  We truly understand that some folks have working dogs (i.e. farmers, ranchers,etc); however, the majority of our dogs have had a rough life prior to coming to us & we want to make sure that they are showered with LUV & maybe even a bit spoiled for the rest of their lives. 

Other facts are also considered, including whether children or other pets are a good fit with the dog. 

Must Luv Dogs reserves the right to deny any applications that we don't think are a good fit with the pup. Our first & foremost concern is the dog's best interest. It is our MISSION to place them in a home that is a great fit for their needs for a lifetime of luv & being part of a family.
*We will consider adoptions in any area; however, will do not ship or transport a puppy under the age of 12 mos. We will ONLY transport an adult dog on a transport approved by MLD, at adopter's expense.
* In order to be affordable and afford every family an opportunity to have a pup of their own, we keep our Adoption Fees at a low $150, but any additional donations are appreciated!

Please note that all of our pets are in private foster homes. In order to reduce any stress or confusion for our pups, we require a completed, approved application BEFORE setting up a meeting for any of fur-babies. Alternatively, you are always welcome to come meet any of our pups at one of our regular Adoption Events. They are always posted on PetFinder OR on our Facebook page: https://www.facebook.com/mustLUVdogs.org.

Finally, THANK YOU for considering Must Luv Dogs for your next pet. 

*Most dogs require a fenced area in yard. 
*Apartments okay IF nearby dog park or walking trails.
*ALL dogs must be INSIDE dogs. 
*We are a DUE DILIGENCE Adoption Rescue.  
*Must have good Vet history & Heartworm prevention is a MUST!
*ALL dogs are fully vetted, spay/neutered and microchipped.

animal.description:
4 SIGNS THAT YOU'RE READY TO FOSTER A DOG!
*You want to help transform a shelter dog into a pet, and help another family find the right dog for their home.
*You’ve been thinking about getting a dog but you’re not sure you’re ready for the lifelong emotional and financial commitment, and you want to get some practice while helping dogs in need.
*You want to give your current dog some canine companionship.
*You have space in your home and schedule to accommodate a temporary guest and give her the attention she needs.
If you nodded in understanding at more than one of the above reasons, you might be ready to foster!

WHAT KINDS OF DOGS GET FOSTERED?
Rescues pull dogs and puppies from shelters who are too stressed out by the shelter environment or need more individual attention than the shelter can provide (including puppies who are too young to be adopted). Shelters have only so much space! Fostering a shelter dog makes space for another,

The most common reasons foster homes are needed are:

*The shelter is overcrowded, and placing dogs in foster care frees up space to save more dogs.
*The rescue group wants to learn more about a dog’s personality and behavior in a home setting.
*A young, energetic dog needs to learn some basic manners before being made available for adoption.
*A shy or timid dog needs a safe place to come out of her shell.
*A dog is recovering from illness or injury.
*A senior or sick dog needs loving hospice care.

THE MAIN FUNCTION OF A FOSTER HOME IS:
to provide a safe, loving home environment. For the most part, this entails caring for your foster as you would care for your own dog: offering food, affection, socialization, and exercise to keep the dog happy and healthy.

As a doggy foster parent, you may also be asked to:

*Transport the dog to and from adoption events.
*Participate in obedience training at home and/or in classes.
*Report back to the rescue with information about the dog’s personality and behavior.
*Speak with potential adopters to tell them about your foster dog and help determine if they are a good match.

FOSTERING SAVES LIVES!
PLEASE CALL/TEXT PAWS RESCUE 727-772-3935

Paws foster program PROVIDES:
FOOD~quality dogfood, food bowls
VETTING~surgery, vaccinations, microchips
FLEA/TICK/HEARTWORM MONTHLY PREVENTATIVES
COLLAR/LEASH
CRATE (if needed)
WE ADVERTISE AND PRESCREEN ALL ADOPTERS
CALL or TEXT 727-772-3935 ASAP PLEASE HELP!!

animal.description:
Beau (AKA Kovu) came into our rescue early last year. He was an energetic 5 month old Treeing Walker Coonhound puppy with a broken foot. He has also been deaf since birth. His family surrendered him when they realized that they could not provide the supervision needed to keep his leg in a cast or afford the additional medical care his injury necessitated. After the bones healed, he needed several months of rehab while on more sedated crate rest. It took several more months wean off medications, work off the stored energy, and learn to be a dog. Beau is now a 60lb, 2 year old handsome pup ready for his forever home.
Beau is a special dog looking for a special person or family. He thrives on routine and is very affectionate with his people. He will bond closely with a strong leader and needs an experienced owner. He likes going on walks and exploring the yard with his nose. He enjoys playing with toys and cuddling with his people. At the end of the day, he likes nothing better than to snuggle next to his person and chew a Nylabone before falling asleep on the couch. Sometimes, he forgets his size and tries to be a lapdog. He has made friends with the resident cats and dogs in his foster home. Being deaf, Beau watches the other dogs for cues. He loves to wrestle when another young foster dog is available but usually respects the senior residents’ boundaries. Beau sleeps in a crate at night and when his people are not home. He rides well in the car and knows to ask to go outside to potty.
Now that Beau is finally ready for adoption, he is looking for a family that has the time, energy, and patience to continue training him, take him on walks, and play with him. He needs a fully fenced yard so he has somewhere safe to run and play. He would love another playful dog in the house. While Beau greatly enjoys the children in his foster home, his play can be too energetic for kids under 12. Beau is crate-trained and house-trained. He knows signs for “sit,” “down,” “come,” “no,” “settle,” “kiss,” and “good boy.” We are working on a few more including “enough” and “stay.” He walks well on a leash using a head collar. Due to his early medical issues, Beau missed out on some socialization time. He can be fearful of strangers outside the home and needs extra time to check out novel objects in his home. However, he has been very excited to meet new people in his foster home. His foster mom has been working with him to improve his stranger reactivity on walks. Although he has already made good progress, his new owner will need to adhere to the same protocols and continue the work. Beau’s forever family must understand this and accept him as he is. While training a deaf hound dog is challenging, it can also be incredibly fulfilling. Beau is very food-motivated and eager to please. He has so much love to give that the effort is well-rewarded.

Beau will not attend adoption events. Prospective adopters will need to meet Beau in his foster home. Please contact Kelly D. by email or text to learn more or to meet Beau. duirkat@gmail.com or 612-642-1424

Adoption Fee: $350   (no checks) 

*REQUIRES FULLY FENCED YARD & NO KIDS UNDER 12 YEARS OLD*

Our fosters do the best they can to provide all information about the animal's background and temperament while in foster care in their home.  An adopters routine and home environment is likely going to be different than that in their foster home.  Sometimes there is more that comes out about a dog's personality once they have been able to settle in a home and truly become comfortable.  There are great articles out there written about the different stages a pet goes through after adoption, discussing transitions that happen at 3 days, 3 weeks, and 3 months.  We highly recommend reading about this - it will help you understand the transition your new pet goes through.   

Last Hope, Inc. is an all volunteer, foster based, no kill rescue! You can see almost all of our dogs on Saturdays from 11-3 at the Burnsville PetSmart and at the Lakeville PetSmart. 

Policies: You do not have to have a fence to adopt a dog from us, but some dogs will require a fence or acres to play, or an active family who will make sure the dog gets the exercise it needs to be happy.  Some dogs do not have the temperament that will do well with young children.   

The Adoption Fee is not enough to cover the vet bills. Sales tax of almost 7.25% is also included in the adoption fee that you see. Please consider donating to Last Hope to help us save these animals!

CAN YOU FOSTER? By taking a dog or puppies into your home temporarily and then coming to our adoption days to help find them homes, we can save more! If interested, please email jaime3369@gmail.com and give us your contact information and what you would like to foster and someone will get back to you! Check our webpage and click the picture of the border collie on the side to learn more about fostering too!

animal.description:
Dodson is a sweet senior who absolutely LOVES people. We expect that he can sense those people who are caring, compassionate, and willing to help him versus those who have subjected him to a life of neglect prior to joining our Safe House..

Dodson is an adorable Pitbull Mix, about 75 lbs and 9 – 10 years old. He’s a stocky boy with a cute waddling walk. He’s a very easy-going and happy boy, especially when he receives lots of attention, petting, and playtime. He enjoys playing with toys, especially balls. 

Dodson would do best as an only dog, so he can receive all the human attention and compassion he so deserves. He slowly warms up to female dogs but is scared and apprehensive around male dogs.

We suspect that, sadly, Dodson appears to be the result of very bad breeding. His front legs are splayed and it might appear he’d have difficulty getting around. However, he does just fine! He does have a little difficulty getting in and out of the car and likely would have some difficulty in a home with a lot of stairs.

Dodson is housebroken, knows his basic manners, and walks nicely on a leash. He is a little nervous when riding in a car but overall does ok.

Dodson is fully vetted, up-to-date on all vaccinations, heartworm negative and on year-round heartworm preventative, neutered, and microchipped for permanent identification.
Please consider providing a loving forever home for Dodson in his twilight years. For more information or to apply to adopt this sweet senior, please contact BAARKDogRescue@gmail.com or 847-852-0895

animal.description:
Hello, my name is Fern and I am a 54#, 3-year-old Pittie/Alaskan Malamute mix beauty.  It's been said I'm wonderful, extremely intelligent, independent, sassy girl with lots of energy. Though I came to the shelter as a stray with an unknown past, they learn new things about me every day, I teach them a few things too.  I'm unsure how I would do living with small animals, as I've a very strong prey drive and incredibly stubborn. They are working on my lack of dog socialization skills, as well as my leash manners.  I'm certainly one of the smartest dogs they have had in this facility.  Due to my energy and need for training, I'm is looking for an adult home only, where my leader continues my routine to unlock my true potential.  I must be the only dog.  I would love a strong and physically active person who would engage my brain on a daily basis. I also like to go on 3+Mile walks everyday, after my walks I take a small break, then back to running around.

Bully/Malamute Breed Experience Required:
Please note, that Fern requires multiple visits with some intensive training to determine if a home visit is possible. Fern appreciates your understanding and patience.

If you have further questions, emails are the only method of communication at this time.  We all care about the health of our 2-legged caregivers and the community at large, so as a precaution we are temporarily suspending our public open hours.  We are still taking email inquiries and applications and will be in touch with you as soon as we are able.  We appreciate everyone’s understanding during this difficult time!  Stay Well!

This 4-year-old Brown Beauty is Belle. The petite pittie pooch is 45 pounds and an absolute dream. She looks to her people for love and reassurance because Belle is a bit shy. This may explain why she is a cuddler extraordinaire! There is one thing Belle likes as much as hugs - toys! She loves toys. Belle loves to be outside and go for car rides. She walks well on a leash and enjoys greeting people in her neighborhood, though she is still very shy when initially meeting them. Belle loves walking in the woods and her confidence has been building while in her foster home. 

Belle has recently learned to use stairs and the awesomeness of a bed. She loves fruits and veggies: Broccoli and carrots are her favorites. When she is excited about something (walks, food, etc.) she gets chatty but she is typically a quiet girl. She is a low maintenance, easy gal.

Belle enjoys leaning firmly against her people and likes a good belly rub. She is just such a love. She is a terrific dog and she is ready to be a part of YOUR family. Do you have a soft spot in your heart and your home for Belle? You can apply to adopt Belle at www.mostlymuttz.org/adoption-application/.

animal.description:
**NO PHONE CALLS PLEASE** ... We are so busy with rescuing and caring for animals and can't return everyone's inquiry. If you are interested in adopting this pet...You must fill out the adoption application at:
http://www.marlcares.org/adopt_app-dog.php  (cut and paste into your browser) 
PLEASE READ all the following info. We do not reply to inquiries asking if the dog is still available, if it is listed here, then it is still available.
 
Karma loves every person and dog she meets. Loves to play and loves toys, loves other dogs.  We pulled her from the Memphis Animal Shelter because they were beyond full and in a critical situation...They called her Karma. 
 She was heartworm positive, but we have started her on the slow kill method and will heartworm treat her.  She is approx 2 to 3 yrs old and weighs approx 50 lbs.  We found out that Karma has 2 bad hips and 2 bad knees...both her knees are torn ....this makes it hard for her to walk so she over compensates with the front and that puts stress and deterioration on her neck, shoulders, and back...as you can imagine...this is a chronic pain situation for her from neck to back knees and bless her heart...she has hid it well... this sweet petite girl wants to live and has tried very hard to live life to it's fullest since rescue.  She has had surgery on her knees and has recovered well, but this will be a chronic situation for her that will always require arthritis meds and supplements for her comfort.  Because of Karma's bad hips and back, she was not a candidate for the typical ACL surgery, but our vets did a modified surgery on her knees to give her some relief and a chance...if we didn't do this surgery then she would have to be euthanized...it would be cruel to keep her in that much chronic and debilitating pain. 

$150 adoption fee, spayed/neutered, microchipped, current vaccinations, and house trained and kennel trained.

ADOPTION APPLICATION:  If you are interested in this pet you must fill out the Adoption Application…which you can find on this site or you can copy and paste this link … http://www.marlcares.org/adopt_app-dog.php    
This does not obligate you in any way.  If this does not work for you then you can email us at midsouthpets@aol.com for one.

PLEASE DO NOT CONTACT US BEFORE READING THE FOLLOWING INFO:  
Your inquiry may not get a reply if you have not read the info we have taken the time to provide.  PLEASE READ about our ADOPTION PROCESS AND REQUIREMENTS provided on this site before contacting us.  You can find it quickly by clicking on our NAME or MORE ABOUT US in the column to the right of this pet’s description.  All your questions can be answered by reading the following info provided below.  Our pets are fostered in the Memphis Area, a tri-state area, TN/AR/MS.  Most are fostered in Red Banks, MS.  

We do not allow meetings with any of our dogs until we have your Adoption Application.  Adopting a new family member should involve a well-thought out and deliberate process. This is not an impulse purchase. Please understand that we do not want these animals to be homeless again. We try to complete the process as quickly as possible and appreciate all the applications and will consider each and every one we receive. 

Filling out the Adoption Application does not obligate you in any way, but simply tells us a little bit about you and whether you and this pet would be a good fit for each other.  We will call you after we receive your application and answer all your questions and talk to you about this pet.  After being approved, we will set up a time to bring the pet to meet you and your family and pets or set up a time for you to meet the pet at the foster home.

NO PHONE CALLS PLEASE.  Rescue is a full time job every day.  Please know because we are so very busy with the dogs along with processing applications, updating webpage’s, rescuing, in many vet appointments, caring for seniors and hospice dogs, etc, etc that we are not able to return phone calls or emails asking if this dog is still adoptable, how much is it to adopt, is it house trained etc…We have included all the info we have on this dog at this current time and update the bio as we learn more about them.  We kennel train all the dogs and will indicate if there are housebreaking issues that we have discovered.  We update our site regularly so if the dog is listed here they are in fact adoptable, but may have applications coming in on them, so if you are interested, you need to get your application in now.

**WE RESERVE THE RIGHT TO REFUSE ANY ADOPTION**  Our first concern is the happiness and welfare of the animal.  We respect our potential adoptors and appreciate your interest in adopting one of our pets.  We care about you too and that you are getting the right fit for your home and lifestyle.  By following our process, together we can make sure you are getting the right pet.**

NOTE: We prefer to adopt in the Mid-South AREA, usually no more than 1-2 hours away in driving distance. It is up to the foster home, how far they are willing to drive. We rarely adopt long distance, but will consider each and every application. 
 
MidSouth Animal Rescue League is an all breed, 501c3, non-profit organization that prefer to rescue senior dogs and special cases.  WE LOVE ROTTWEILERS...With 20 years of experience with our beloved ROTTWEILER breed, and little help for this breed in our area, we try to focus on rescuing them and try not to ever have to turn any away that need us…especially the seniors that end up in shelters.  Currently, we have several senior rottweilers in our hospice foster program.  We always need more fosters so that we never have to say NO to them or other seniors.  

We have also started a community relief effort specifically in the Red Banks, MS area not far from us, called The Dog House Project, where we go door to door providing dog houses to dogs on chains and other dogs and cats without proper shelter, including straw in cold temps, as well as food and other supplies as needed.   We offer free spay/neuter services to those animals and continue to check on them all year.  To date many have been spayed and neutered and some have been surrendered from their neglected lives on chains.  We are making a difference and need your donations to continue this program.  We always need igloo type dog houses.  

MidSouth Animal Rescue League relies on the kindness, generosity, and financial support of people like you so that we can continue to rescue and care for dogs like this one. We are a group of dedicated volunteers who respond to animals in need in shelters, strays, and from individuals. We receive no federal or state funds and are supported solely by private donations. 

Many of the animals we save are in need of special medical care or surgery to bring them back to health before they can be placed. Veterinary care, vaccinations, tests, x-rays, medications, spay and neutering, heartworm prevention, flea/tick prevention, worming, food, kennels, grooming, and other supplies are provided for each dog while in our care.

animal.description:
"Trust the process. Your time is coming." My name is Rossi and I just know that my time is coming. My time to find my forever home, that is! I have experienced some things in my 4 years that have made me slow to trust, but for anyone willing to show me some patience, I will be the best friend you've ever known. I guess I should start this off by telling you a little more about myself. I'm a 60 pound Black Mouth Cur/Shepherd mix. I am looking for a home without kids or cats because both are too scary for me. I like other dogs though, and would love to have a respectful and playful dog friend in my forever home. I also need a home with a privacy fenced yard so that we have a safe place for some playtime and exercise while we get to know one another. My perfect forever human needs to be someone who is able to provide me with structure and boundaries so that I can follow their lead. You see, I am really just a sweet and submissive boy, but without a strong leader I sometimes try to be the leader and that makes me all kinds of nervous; I would so much rather follow your lead! Once we have that forever bond, I would love to join you on some outdoor adventures, as I love to join my foster family on walks and hikes! If you think it might be time for a sweet boy like me in your life, then fill out that adoption application today.

My adoption fee is $150 and includes my spay/neuter, vaccinations, wellness exam, heartworm test, and microchip! Thank you for your inquiry. Pickles has an adopter but we have to wait for them to go pick him up after the stay at home is lifted.  Once he is picked up we will remove his profile. Please do not write to us for an application. Sorry for any inconvenience.

+++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++







Meet Pickles!  Pickles is a fun loving, good natured cutie with great expressive ears and a soft coat.  He is about 2 1/2 years old and 8 lbs. 

Pickles may be a tiny guy but he comes with a big personality.  He loves to be loved and when you go to pet him he immediately rolls on his back and wiggles around. Pickles is great with everyone, of all ages.  Humans aren’t the only ones he gets along with!  He runs, wrestles and chases the other fosters dogs in the house and he gets along well with them.  Pickle lives with cats but he has been known to chase them around the house.

Pickles is mostly house trained with few accidents and he usually goes on the pee pads. He could use some help getting it down pat.  He also knows a few commands and comes when you call his name but like some rescue dogs, this smartie just needs a little time and consistency to master it all.  

Pickles is quite inquisitive and excited for life.  He loves to bathe in the sun, look for squirrels and ensure you are safe from strangers.  But when night falls, Pickles loves to bury himself in blankets and burrow in the bed under some covers.  He has no problem through the night and just wants to be near to you. Are you the one to give him the life he deserves?  

Pickles wouldn’t do well left alone for a full work day and would like to have a canine companion if his parents are gone that long. He would do fine with no other dog as long as someone was around during the day.

Pickles is being fostered in Napa. CA.  His adoption fee is $275.00.

All our dogs are in private foster homes and arrangements to meet our dogs occur after an application has been received.

If you would like to know more about this sweet boy or receive an application to adopt, please contact us at Dogzonerescue@yahoo.com.

animal.description:
Honey came to us with an injury that seems to be from being hit by a car.  No broken bones but she had some type of muscle and nerve damage in her right from leg.  She came to us not being able to use it much at all with open soars on her leg and head.  After getting xrays and having a few visits to Veterinarians we came to the conclusion to try to rehabilitate her leg on our own instead of amputating her leg.  

The sores on her head and leg have completely headed but we still deal with some on her foot from her dragging it at times.  We have tired chiropractic care, we are now trying water therapy, and plan to try acupuncture and micro current therapy next.  She has gotten a lot of movement back in her leg and seems to be getting some nerve response back as well.  She couldn't feel her food up to the sore on her wrist area for a while.  Now she seems to be responding to stimulation between her outside two toes.  She is improving!!!

Honey is a great girl.  She is very attentive to everything around her.  She acts a bit neurotic when it comes to lasers or any kind of flash of light.  Sometimes shadows get her excited too.  She loves to chase the flashlight at night.  She loves to play chase with her fur foster siblings and steal the toys from them just to loose interest and move on to another toy quickly.  She is loves to go swimming at The Water Bark where we do water therapy.  She loves tennis balls and will do anything for a treat!  

If you would like to come visit or adopt Honey please visit out website at www.shannonfarmz.com and fill out an adoption application.  Honey is not yet spayed but will be before adopted.  She is fully vaccinated, wormed regularly, and microchipped.  If you have any questions please email us at info@shannonfarmz.com

animal.description: Needs: • Active Canine Pal • Large, Physically Fenced Yard • No Young Children. Please read Lassie's requirements in a forever home below and only inquire/apply if you fit that criteria. Lassie is a precious 1.5 year old, 47 lb. Collie/Australian Shepherd mix. With her always wagging tail and love of people and friends, this girl is a true delight! She loves dancing around with her toys and is all about having fun. Lassie loves playing with the other dogs in her foster home, though true to breed, can also be seen trying to herd them. Intelligent and adventurous, she would love a home that will both mentally and physically stimulate her. She enjoys swimming in her foster family’s pool and can often be found stealing tennis balls from her canine friends who play fetch in the water. When Lassie crashes for a nap, she likes to curl up on the couch or a lounge chair on the deck and simply melts into a scrumptious cuddle buddy. She also sleeps in bed with her foster parents every night. Lassie is house trained, walks well on a leash, and knows how to sit and come when instructed. A vocal girl, she makes the most precious happy noises and loves to chat with her human and canine friends. With the energy level and mouthiness of an Australian Shepherd, Lassie is not suitable for a home with cats or young children. She would enjoy a home with a large fenced yard and another active dog to play with. Please note that Lassie has hip dysplasia and will only be adopted to a home that continues giving her daily (over the counter) Moboflex, CBD and fish oil and prescription pain medication on an as needed basis. Thank you so much for your interest in adopting a dog from A New Chance Animal Rescue (https://anewchancear.org). We are a 501c3, tax deductible organization. ANCAR is a foster-based rescue, and we adopt within a 90 mile radius of Bedford Hills, NY. You will find the adoption application here: (https://anewchancear.org/adopt/adoption-application/). All fields on the application must be completed. Please read about the adoption process (https://anewchancear.org/adopt/adoption-process/) so you'll know what to expect when you submit. Our dogs are in foster care and we do NOT have a shelter or boarding facility. AN APPLICATION MUST BE COMPLETED IN FULL AND APPROVED BEFORE A DOG CAN BE MET. This is a firm policy. Our busy volunteers are not able to respond to questions about the dog or dog meeting requests in the absence of an application. We know these dogs very well because they are in foster care. Please read the profiles of the dog(s) you are interested in prior to submitting an application. If there are specific requirements stated (ie: Fenced Yard or Canine Friend Required) these are included because they are vital to the happiness, health, safety and adoption success of that dog. We are only able to save as many dogs as we have foster homes (https://anewchancear.org/foster/faqs/) and resources for. We provide medical care including vaccinations, testing, deworming, spaying/neutering and microchipping before transporting our dogs. We provide all supplies, preventatives and any follow up vet care necessary while they are in foster care. These costs are high and the number of lives we can save is entirely dependent upon donations from people like you. We do not receive funding from private foundations or government sources. If you can find room in your heart to help us, with any amount, we are truly grateful (https://anewchancear.org/help/donate/). We are a 501c3 organization, so all donations are tax-deductible. It is only through the kindness of supporters like you that we are 'changing lives...one tail at a time' by providing our dogs with 'A New Chance.' (https://anewchancear.org) Thanks so much.

animal.description:
Trix is a 7 year old female Shih Tzu rescued from a puppy mill.
Shortly after her rescue we noticed a large mass on her stomach. We scheduled a removal and biopsy and unfortunately it was a very invasive form of cancer. While the vet was able to remove the tumor entirely, it is very likely that she will develop others. We check her tummy daily for any new lumps or bumps, which is easy to do because Trix LOVES having her belly rubbed. She has come a very long way since her rescue and she will even dance and kick her feet when she wants attention. New people still make her nervous and she will require a family with patience who will understand she needs to trust you before she opens up. Never approach Trix from behind, she is easily startled and will snip. We believe a house without small children would be ideal for Trix. She loves treats but still doesn’t take them directly from our hands. She will play with toys occasionally. She does fine with cats. She is an older dog so she can get grumpy towards the younger fosters when she doesn’t want to be bothered. She does enjoy sitting in your lap for short periods of time. She is a very sweet girl and will make a great companion dog with just a little time and patience. 

If you think you would be interested, please complete our no obligation application and we can start the process at www.luv4k9s.org. Select Available Dogs then scroll down to application, complete and submit. 

A physical secure fence attached to the residence is a requirement to adopt a dog from our rescue. Invisible fence doesn't meet this requirement. No exceptions.

Our adoption area is primarily OHIO. We will consider KENTUCKY, AND INDIANA AND CERTAIN AREAS OF MICHIGAN, WEST VIRGINIA, AND PENNSYLVANIA. 

WE DO NOT SHIP NOR ARRANGE TRANSPORTS.

THE APPLICATION MUST BE COMPLETED AND SUBMITTED BEFORE WE CAN START THE PROCESS. 

IT CAN TAKE AT LEAST 2 WEEKS TO PROCESS AN APPLICATION SOMETIMES LONGER DEPENDING ON VOLUNTEER AVAILABILITY AND NUMBER OF APPLICATIONS RECEIVED SO PLEASE BE PATIENT. 

NOTE TO EMAILERS FROM PETFINDER: WE DO NOT RESPOND TO EMAIL INQUIRIES WITHOUT AN APPLICATION. WE REGRET WE CANNOT RESPOND TO EVERY EMAIL, BUT UNLESS YOU FILL OUT AN APPLICATION, WE DO NOT KNOW YOU EXIST. 

All known information about an individual dog is provided in its listing. We do our best to provide accurate information, but adopters must understand that each home is different, and the dog may behave differently in a new home. Dogs are creatures of their environment and you help make the dog what it will be. 
Homes considering adopting a puppy must be prepared for:
1.) Flexible schedules for potty training. Puppies can only hold it for one hour per month of age (ex. a 4 month old puppy can only go 4 hours without a potty break) 
2.) Crate training until the puppy is at least one year old, to prevent chewing on inappropriate things when you can't supervise.
3.) Socialization: The more positive and varying experiences as a puppy the better, both in and out of your home.
4.) Puppy behavior and life stages are equivalent to a human toddler. It takes at least a full year to have a calmer, well-adjusted dog. Patience is required and when your dog's behavior is a positive experience for you and those around you, your patience will be rewarded tenfold, for years to come.
Please do not consider adopting a puppy if you have not thoroughly thought through the pros and cons of having one. So many people end up returning them after 3-5 months because they didn't realize the amount of work involved in raising a puppy. Patience, appropriate toys, socialization, and obedience training are all musts. All are time consuming and can be expensive. All Dogs Require supervision with children and obedience training. Adopters that want to have good dogs must be prepared to put the time and effort into training a dog. Any dog requires work and effort, but a well-trained, well socialized dog is more than worth the effort put in to get them there. 

Our adoption fee includes spay/neuter, routine shots, rabies, worming, microchipped, heartworm testing and they are on monthly preventative. Visit our website www.luv4k9s.org for more information and to complete an application.

animal.description:
These two sweet older brothers are looking for someone with a big heart to give them a loving home. They came to Best Friends in January 2019 and are both neutered and up to date on vaccinations. Their dad was an older gentleman that lived in the city and did not have any family. Unfortunately, he passed away right around Christmas time and he did not have anyone checking on him. When someone finally did check on him, they found that he had passed away in his bed and his two sweet dogs were laying by his side watching over him. They love to lay together and do well with other dogs. They are currently staying with our loving staff at our Joppa location but want so badly for someone to give them a comfortable loving home.

Rusty is around 11. He acts like a puppy in a very senior body. He has trouble walking and will need a splint changed every few months at around $250. Chocky is mellow and around 12.   They are both 50-60 pounds and are pretty relaxed most of the time.  Rusty is the more vocal of the two and he vocalizes when he is excited, like when visitors come and at feeding time.  Rusty is on pain management for the rest of his life and tolerates it well.  Chocky is overall healthy for his age.  Both do have some age related issues such as joint pain.  Chocky does occasionally have a gastro upset.  They are very bonded and must stay together. They cannot go home with little dogs or cats.

animal.description:
Red is a sweet, retired senior, 10 years old, Blue Tick-Bloodhound mix dog and long-time shelter resident. Sometimes the shy guy - he is playful and affectionate once he gets to know you. Mellow now, in his senior years - he enjoys walks on or off-leash. And he likes playing with toys and fetching balls. Red has been at the shelter almost 4 years. He was surrendered in 2015. And while he has adopted us as his own and is comfortable here; he deserves a family and home of his own in his twilight years. The shelter is not the same as a home and long winter evenings at the shelter can be lonely and boring; sometimes loud and unsettling with new dogs in nearby kennels. We wish for Red to have warm, quiet companionable evenings in a home of his own. He is low maintenance and was trusted inside in his former home. If you are looking for a faithful, mellow solo side-kick, Red is your dog.

He aint heavy, hes our Red. Red can be shy towards people and keep his distance until he gets to know you, which means he doesnt always show well to potential adopters. Once he trusts you he will stay by your side. He can encounter other dogs out and about and greet, but does not seem to get along with other dogs long-term; and Red cannot go to a home with cats. While situation dependent; Red will mostly likely need his new home to have a fenced yard.

animal.description:
Journey loves most people, but she prefers females. She will need some time to get to know you and to trust you.  It would be best for her to be the only dog in a household where she can get all the love and attention she deserves. Journey thrives with calmer people so a household without young children would be ideal for her.  She is not the type of dog who wants to go for long leisurely walks...she is completely content to have a yard to chase her jolly ball,  a kiddie pool to splash in, and someone to give her endless amounts of belly rubs.  Journey has some cattle dog in her so she loves having a job to do or play any game that challenges her.   She has been working with trainers on her manners and, where she used to resist training,  she now loves it!!! 

Her date of birth is 7/8/2017 and she weighs about 30 pounds. 

*We did receive a donated Wisdom Panel DNA test for Journey and we found out she is: 37.5% Standard Bulldog, 25% American Staffordshire Terrier, 25% Australian Cattle Dog, and 12.5% Breed Groups: Terrier & Companion.

If you have been looking for a playful, sweet, small dog, submit an adoption application for Journey at http://www.fayettefcar.com/applicationform, where you can also review FCAR’s adoption requirements.

All FCAR adoptable dogs have been spayed or neutered, are current on all vaccines, on flea/tick and heartworm prevention, microchipped, and come with a 30-day pet health guarantee. The adoption fee is $95 with an approved application. A fenced yard is required for Journey.

animal.description:
This pretty girl is a 4-year-old lab/pit mix. Cricket is a wonderful companion to people in her home. She is smart, listens well, and is delighted by affection, especially belly rubs. Her potty training is perfect and she is cooperative when crating is needed. Although she is a bit slow to warm up to new people, the pay-off for giving her time is her trust and adoration.
Crickets ideal situation will be a relatively quiet home without lots of visitors, a sizable yard with at least a 5-foot fence, adopters who are willing to keep an eye on her when she is in the yard, either no other dogs or a male dog who is interested in having a companion, and no cats. If leash walking is desired, she will need an experienced person who can help her manage her reactivity to dogs and squirrels she sees on the street. Otherwise, she is happy to get her exercise by exploring and running in her yard.

All dogs are spayed/neutered, up to date on vaccinations, heartworm tested negative and microchipped. A dogs adoption fee is $200. There is a $5 fee for credit/debit cards.

Peanut was pulled from the Vermilion Parish Rabies Animal Control on August 6, 2016 and has been waiting for his forever family to find him. Peanut loves to go for walks and love to play with toys. He is around 3 years old and has tons of spunk and sass with a quirky personality. Peanut needs a strong authority figure or he will push buttons just to see how much he can get away with. But with the right guidance, Peanut is a terrific boy eager to please his owners. Peanut is fully vetted, kennel trained, and house trained.

To adopt Peanut, complete the adoption application at AAVArescue.com

animal.description:
*** Sweet Stella can ONLY be adopted in the NY/NJ area. She was born around the summer of 2018. Approximately 55lbs. Possibly a Black Mouth Cur Mix.*** adoption instructions below

In order to adopt Stella you must agree to meet with her and her trainer in NJ on at least 3 separate occasions, both with and without your dog if applicable. 

See Stella on The Dodo at: https://www.facebook.com/thedodosite/videos/1376367309191892/

Stella came to us when we got an urgent plea from a good Samaritan to take a dog belonging to an estranged relative. This poor pup was being kept in a back room, chained to an old broken mattress, often with no food or water. Being a large, energetic puppy, she was often difficult to handle, but rather than trying to train her, Stella had been beaten when she made mistakes. She was one of the saddest and most depressing examples of neglect we had ever seen. 

Stella shows just how resilient a pupper can be. Think of her as a shy Party girl.

After gaining her health and strength back, she spent several months living in a special board and train facility where she learned manners and how to greet people in a polite way - as well as learning a lot about life itself. Shes learned that humans can be and are loving towards her, and in turn shes learned she can hang out calmly. However she still is (and will always be) FULL of energy and would love a very active family.

Her early years have left her with certain behavioral issues around impulse control and meeting new friends which she, with the help of her new family, will need to continue to work on for some time. However this sweet princess wants more than anything to please the humans she knows and trusts. Once shes comfortable, she just wants to have a good time.

After training camp, Stella was taken in by an amazing foster family who are continuing her training and medication program. She also gets to spend lots of time playing with her foster dog brother and her outlook in life is so joyful.

Stella will always need a special environment, though, with forever parents who are willing to help her learn about the world at her pace. She will do best in a home with no small children as she can be overly exuberant when unsure.

That said, with a few slow introductions Stella can and in fact SHOULD live with another dog if possible. The ideal family would be one where someone is home most of the time or can bring her to an appropriate day camp program. 

Stella still goes back to training camp from time to time and sees a special behavioral vet who proscribes her medication to help her deal with some of her anxiety behaviors. 

Her camp carer says, Stella is having a great time at camp! She is always curious about new smells and enjoys the company of her human friends. She loves to run when she's in the big yard and enjoy the tranquil sounds at times. Stella is such a beauty and we love having her here at camp. She's got personality and energy for miles and thats one of our favorite things about her. Stella has so much personality; she is silly, full of so much excitement and energy. She also can be super sweet and whenever she sees you coming toward her, her butt just wont stop wiggling! 

If you think you can give Stella all the love she deserves and would like to meet her, please go to Petstablished.com or follow the link below to complete an application to adopt. All of our animals are in foster homes. For the sake of our animals and foster families, you must have an approved application with references before you can meet them. 

https://petstablished.com/pets/public/379676

In order to receive a speedy response to any inquiry, please email us directly at Info@ShelterChic.org or check out our website ShelterChic.org where you will find the answer to most questions about our adoption process and fees. Please remember that our organization is run entirely by volunteers in our spare time, and emails are responded to in order of importance. If you do not hear from us and cannot find the information needed on our website or in our animals profile, please reach out to us again. For more images and tales of our pets in foster-care check out our social media pages @shelterchic 

***PLEASE DO NOT email to ask if the animal you are interested in is still available. Just check Petstablished, if they are there, they are available! Please note that 3rd party adoption sites take 6-12 hours to refresh. Allpaws.com and petharbor.com are 4+ months out of date. We are not associated with Petcurious.com in anyway. Please do not apply for animals you see there without checking they are on the Petstablished website first.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
MISSY MAE STEAL YOUR HEART. Missy Mae is a friendly Chihuahua mix with a cute little snaggle tooth. She is nearly 10 years old, in good health and weighs about 14 pounds. Missy Mae loves car rides and her squeaky/chewy toys. She's house- and leash trained, and actually enjoys time to herself, so owners who work outside the home would be fine so long as they keep in mind that she has a tiny bladder. She does not get along with other pets or children. Missy Mae would be very happy with a single person or a pair of empty nesters/retirees.

Missy Mae is spayed, heartworm negative, microchipped and up to date on her vaccinations. She is affectionate but sometimes she also needs her space and might seem standoffish. She enjoys going for walks but needs to avoid other dogs. In return for a quiet home with patient, loving people, Missy Mae will be a fun and loving companion for years to come. Her adoption fee is being covered by a TDR Angel.
Available at Tired Dog Rescue in Gulfport, MS. Visit the website to complete an application, www.tireddogrescue.com

Recap

Breed: Chihuahua

Age: 10 years (best estimate)

Weight: 14 lbs.

Spayed: yes

Fence required: no

Child friendly: no

Pet friendly: no

animal.description: The rescue community tends draws out some of the very best humans on the planet. The kind of humans who can see the hope in a dog's eyes who hasn't had an easy road. The kind who love so deeply, they would move mountains for an animal in need of grace. Rezendez really, really needs one of those kind of humans. We found him a local shelter where he'd been rescued from a life outside, with no shelter, on the end of a heavy chain. His world was small and the humans in it were not kind. Now that he's safe with us, we hope Rezendez can get a second chance with someone worthy of his trust and love. He would do best in a quiet, adult home with someone who will give him the time and space to settle in and feel at home. He's got a nice, even energy and seems to like other dogs. If you have a dog who can show him the ropes, that might be exactly what he needs. If you're looking for a dog you can help, we would love to see this gentle, loving boy find his happy ever after.
