animal.description: Parker is a handsome 6 to 7-year-old hound-bully breed mix that comes to Westport Animal Control after being abandoned on a cold, sleety day in Westport.  While he needs a bit of time to get to know strangers, some walks and yummy treats are the way to his heart.  He is loving and affectionate with staff and volunteers.  He wants to give hugs and is quite a leaner too.  He is quite charming.  He quite enjoys playing with toys and is happy to plop them in your lap to be thrown.  After a tumultuous life, we are sure, Parker is reclaiming his doggie joy, and we are so happy to help in that regard.  He has tested well with other dogs - once he gets over his initial excitement.  For additional photos and videos, please visit WASA's FB at:  http://www.facebook.com/westportwasa.  For additional information about Parker, please contact WASA by calling 203 557 0361 or by sending an email to wasa1@optonline.net.

Marvin
Breed: Sheperd mix
Gender: Male
Age: 2 years old
Size: Large
Where you can find me: At WAG
Energy Level: High
Training Goals: Sitting still while you put my harness on, gaining confidence with new places and new people. Marvin will need mandatory training session booked in with a WAG approved trainer.
House trained? Yes
Kids? No
Cats? No
Dogs? I would like to be the only dog in the house and can get excited when I see dogs on walks. I get along only with some dogs and in the right situations.
Medical Needs: Anxiety medication

My Perfect Match:

-Has a safe a secure fenced yard. I may never be a candidate for being off leash or going to public parks and dog parks as I get overwhelmed easily.

-Is willing to take a few trips to WAG to get to know me before taking me home. I am fearful of strangers when I first meet them.

-Has experience with fearful dogs. My reactions to my fears can include trying to run away (I am very strong!) or flattening myself to the ground and not wanting to move!

-Has lots of patience and understanding of my past - I did not develvope in a normal environment so my needs are different than your average dog.

-Loves goofy loveable quirky boys. I am so much fun to play with when I feel safe and can be off leash in a secure area. I love to play fetch and tug-of-war and soccer, and have lots of energy!

-Will continue with my training and keep me on leash. My training needs will be more about confidence building and creating positive associations rather than basic commands.

-Will buy me a GPS tracker that I must wear on walks to keep me safe! I am a flight risk so this is a requirment.

-Is strong! I am strong 

-Will love me forever no matter what!

 

About Me:
-I LOVE to play with any ball of any size!

-I love to swim, any time of the year.

-I am very busy but am learning to relax with the help of medication.

-I am very shy meeting new people, you may need to meet me a few times before we are friends.

-I am still nervous going on walks and would like a quiet yard in my new home.

-I need lots of gentle training.

-I am nervous of loud noises and new things and will need someone who is patient with me.

-I have never lived in a home before.

APPLY FOR MARVIN!
My Story:
I was surrendered to WAG after my previous family could no longer take care of me. I was left outside a lot, my owners no longer had the time for me. I hope to find an amazing new home that is excited to have me as a member of the family! Primary Color: Brown Brindle Weight: 29.4kg Age: 3yrs 11mths 3wks Animal has been Neutered
animal.name: Marvin

animal.description:
Notes on Sweet Pea from her foster: " Loves cuddling. Loves adventure. Is shy to try new things, but once she does has a blast. 
Total people pleaser. A little shy at first (probably because of history before rescued). But then when she comes out of her bubble she's so much fun! 
Learns very quickly. I taught her sit, stay, shake, and come all in one days worth of training. (And I'm not a great trainer! ?) 
Can be full of energy, or completely down to earth depending on the human's mood."

My adoption fee covers 3 rounds of parvo/distemper shots, my bordatella, my rabies shot, my spay, my microchip, heartworm test and the flea and heartworm preventative treatment I've been on since I entered this great program!

Since NKHC requires a home check (we arent inspecting your life. Just wanna make sure it's safe ie: not a hoarding situation, a reasonable way to walk the doggy without throwing it on the highway, things like that) we do not adopt further than a reasonable driving distance (2.5 hours max).

animal.description:
Adoptable Remy is one of the lucky dogs at our shelter who is currently in a foster home. This has given us some very valuable information to share with interested adopters:
1. She prefers to be called by her full name, Remy The Double Stuff Oreo. (Remy is a bit chonky so she is currently on a diet. Her ideal Oreo size is single-stuff, around 45-50 lbs).
2. Remy is a world class snuggler. She loves to plop herself next to you, roll over with her feet in the air, and fall asleep while you rub her tummy.
3. Remy walks well using a harness.
4. She wants to be an acrobat when she grows up. She's been practicing her somersaults-into-a-beetle-dance routine and it's really coming along!
5. When she sees someone she knows, her entire back end wiggles like it's going to just dance right off her body.
6. Remy is FANTASTIC in her crate. She is crated periodically throughout the day and at night to sleep, and doesn't make a peep!
7. Remy definitely still has some puppy energy at approximately 3 years old but tires out pretty easily. She snorts in her sleep like a little piglet.
8. Remy is house-trained.
Her foster parents describe Remy as "a real sweetheart" and "super easy" and "an endearing little imp." All she needs is her very own person! If you are interested in giving Remy a home, please email us at info@carolinehumane.org or call us at 410.820.1600.

animal.description: Ricky was adopted to a married couple 11 years ago. When the husband passed away a few years ago, he started acting out by urinating in the house. Because the owner had three other dogs she decided she could not deal with him and took him to animal control. We were devastated to find out he was there and immediately rescued him. He is 13 years old and would not likely get adopted. We have had him checked over by our vet and he is in good health . We believe his potty habits changed because he missed the owner. We haven't had him long yet, but he is not skittish anymore and is starting to give kisses now that he is getting attention. Sometime that's all is needed is a loving home. Picture up soon.

Meet Blue, a loyal, playful dog in search of his forever family. Blue is very playful, as he loves to pay fetch with practically any toy. His favorites, though, are plush squeaker toys. He knows commands such as sit, stay, drop, and leave it when playing. Blue also enjoys going for walks with his people. He is very polite when walking on a leash. Blue is becoming very mannerly and practices good listening skills. 

Blue does enjoy low-key times. When he isn't playing, you would love to be hanging out with his forever family. He is very loyal. Blue likes to stay close to the action, but he doesn't need much affection. You can find Blue wherever his people are. 

Blue is house trained. He is also crate trained, although he does just fine when he is left alone. Blue would thrive in a home in which he is the only pet. He would also prefer a home with older children or no children, as he often gets nervous. 

Blue is currently located at the Sanctuary in Marion, WI. If you're interested in making him part of your family, please complete an online application. Our adoption team will review it. When an application is approved, we will be in touch to schedule a time for you to meet him.

animal.description:
Meet Will, a happy boy in search of his forever home. Will has the most adorable smile and wants to make everyone around him happy. Will likes to be close to his people but doesn't need a lot of affection. Will wants a home that can give him the essentials. Because of Will's maturity, he prefers low-key days. He doesn't need a lot of toys and doesn't need to be the center of attention. Will does enjoy the occasional stroll around the neighborhood, though. This old man still likes to get out and be rambunctious! 

They say you can't teach an old dog new tricks, but Will is proving them wrong! Will knows basic commands such as sit and stay. He is also working on his manners. He wants to put in the effort with his forever family in exchange for all of his love. 
Will's perfect home would be one in which he is the only pet. He's looking for a patient family because he is unsure about most things. He will need some help adjusting to a crate but will do best crated when he is left alone. He occasionally gets nervous or will have a potty accident when left alone. 

Wil is currently located at the Sanctuary in Marion, WI. If you're interested in making Will part of your family, please complete an online application. Our adoption team will review it. When an application is approved, we will be in touch to schedule a time for you to meet him.

animal.description:
Egon arrived in rescue from a hoarder situation and is slowly learning to trust humans and feel safe. The psychological damage to Egon was severe. With the help of his dedicated foster mom, Kristine, he has been learning how to be a dog instead of a ghost flitting around scared constantly. The process can be long and involved, but seeing the progress inch by inch is so rewarding. He's working on recovering in our Make Me Brave program and he's already revealed a quirky and fun side, despite his shyness. We look forward to discovering more about this 4 year old boy as he improves his socialization skills with humans.

YOU CAN SPONSOR EGON'S CARE IN RESCUE BY CLICKING ON THE SPONSOR BUTTON ON THIS PAGE or DIRECTLY ON THE RESCUE'S WEBSITE: www.onmywayhomerescue.com.  Thank you so very much for caring and supporting our rescue mission!

animal.description:
Meet Betty!

ATTENTION: PLEASE READ THROUGH TO SEE WHETHER YOU MEET OUR ADOPTION CRITERIA BEFORE RESPONDING. IF YOU MEET OUR CRITERIA FOR ADOPTION OF THIS DOG, PLEASE FOLLOW THE LINK TOWARD THE BOTTOM OF THE PROFILE TO COMPLETE OUR APPLICATION. THANK YOU!

We don’t know for sure what breed mix Betty is, but we made our best guess. Betty is a stunning, young, athletic and energetic dog who is enthusiastic about everything. She loves to sprint, wrestle, jog, fetch, hike, swim, camp...and then snuggle all night long. She is insecure about meeting new people or dogs on leash, but once she breaks the ice, she is a real sweetie and a lighthearted goofball. Her foster mom’s favorite things to do with Betty is to throw balls into the waves on the Oregon coast for Betty to retrieve, and to rest her head on Betty like a big furry pillow. 

Betty needs a home with someone who is as active and energetic as she is. She  needs a home with adults only, and needs someone with previous dog ownership experience. She can only go to a home with another active young dog who likes to run and wrestle and share their toys with her and a yard with a tall, secure fence. Betty isn’t aggressive towards cats, but most kitties would find her obnoxious and overwhelming. Betty is potty trained and crate trained, but shouldn’t be left alone all day long while her human family members work a 9-5 schedule. 

Betty is a smart cookie who loves to be challenged. She enjoys K9 Nosework (sniffing games) and agility classes, and has completed obedience training at Sit Means Sit. In fact, Sit Means Sit has offered her new owner complimentary training sessions!!! 

Adoption Process: We are not first come first served. Indigo Rescue focuses on finding good matches between dogs and families to ensure life long adoptions. We deliver all dogs to their new homes. All of our dogs are in foster homes. 

If you’re interested in meeting one of our dogs, please use the following link and complete our Adoption Application. You can either scan your completed application and email it to us at: info@indigorescue.org, or you can fax it to us at: 888-502-7660.
The link is not live, so you will need to copy and paste it into your browser: https://storage.googleapis.com/gator-users/user-680788/documents/d1742bff02e44c2ea25649cb45df5103/Pet%20Application%20Form%20December%202020.pdf

If the dog you're interested in seems compatible with your lifestyle we'll set up a time for you to meet the dog privately.
PLEASE NOTE: Indigo Rescue only adopts to homes within 30 miles of Beaverton because our volunteers deliver all of our dogs to their adoptive homes. We work very hard to create a family of our Indigo Rescue adopters because we want to be close enough to help in case there are any problems. We want everyone to be happy and successful!

**ALL of our dogs, puppies, cats, kittens and rabbits come vaccined to their age, spayed/neutered and microchipped.

Thank you for your interest in adopting and saving a life.

Roses are red, violets are blue, this Rose is the sweetest - and she’s waiting for you!

This beautiful girl was found on Valentine’s Day running down a busy road.  It was clear that Rose had been on the streets for a while but she’s come a long way since then. Rose is ready and waiting to meet her forever family!

*  Rose is a sweetheart who loves attention from her humans! She enjoys cuddles, belly rubs, and snuggling up as close as she can.

*  Rose is a smart girl! She seems to be housetrained and does well when left home alone. She already knows how to sit on command! 

*  Rose is adventurous and playful! Her favorite thing to do is explore on walks. She knows how to walk well on a leash. She also loves to play with toys with her human companions.

*  Rose is an easy-going pup! She is a quiet girl with a calm temperament

*  Rose isn’t a big fan of other dogs so she’d prefer to be the only one in your life!

Rose is incredibly affectionate and playful with her humans. She would do well in a home that can appreciate her moderate activity level and cuddly nature.  Her ideal day would include some play time with toys, a nice long walk, and lots and lots of love! If Rose sounds like a good match for you, apply to meet her today!

animal.description: You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.This stunning boy is Justus, a Pit mix born in 2015, who came into rescue from Texas - found chained, with no fur, eyes filled with mucus, skin raging from infection from neglect and abuse, unable to use his back legs and left on a blanket to die. An MRI determined that blunt force trauma caused a fracture to his spine that was never treated. With intensive physical therapy, our strong-willed warrior with the now-gorgeous coat is running, playing and ready for a home of his own! Justus absolutely adores his humans, including older children, but needs to be the only pet in his home. And he is reactive to loud noises, so his home should be in a quiet suburb with a yard. He is neutered and up to date on vaccines. If you are the special someone who can finally show Justus what it's like to be loved unconditionally, never to be abandoned or mistreated ever again, please fill out an adoption application here! Http://www.rescuedogsrocknyc.org

animal.description:
The name is Kristoph and I am a big boy who is believed to have turned five late 2020.  I like the ladies and will take time warming up to the men.  The male volunteers are my buddies and I enjoy my walks with them now that I know them.  I know I'm handsome and that makes me very attractive to potential adopters.  

Not much is known about my background.  I enjoy the great outdoors and watching the birds and squirrels and nature in general.  Being a big boy, I will need a tall, secure fence.  Why am I still at AGPR?  I am VERY protective and take my guardian role very seriously.  I do not care for visitors or any of the delivery trucks.  And barking is my favorite past time if there are things moving or making noise in (or outside) of my yard.

My future family wish list?  I would love a big yard to run around in and prefer no children (I'm afraid I'll knock them over).  I'm not fond of visitors so a home with kids with visiting friends or very active and social adults might not be the right environment for me.  I also want a calm household where I can eat my meals in peace. Not sure if other household pets are going to make me happy - just not sure. I am not a Pyr for just anyone...I need big dog confident adults only.  

All Great Pyrenees require a fenced-in yard (at least four foot high). If you have questions about the breed or our adoption policies and procedures, please go to our website at www.agprescue.org. There's plenty of good information about the breed on our website - Pyrs aren't a breed for everyone! 

Our adoption application is online: http://agprescue.org/adoption-application/agpr-application-donations/

Please note that we are a small regional rescue organization. We will consider adopting to families within a four to five hour drive to Richmond, VA

animal.description:
Do I look familiar?  You may have seen me on Facebook a couple years ago when my friends at AGPR were looking for help in paying for my super new cart.  My name is Nala and we think I'm about 8 years old.  My previous owners were going through difficult times and had to give me up.

My back legs got a bit messed up when I was younger and they never got fixed.  The specialist said that "they are what they are" and there's no fix.  BUT, my cart is my best friend!  Put those wheels on and watch me go...zoom, zoom.  Squirrels, deer - watch out!

I'm a flirt.  I am partial to male dogs...if they are nice and not bossy.  My buddies at AGPR tell me I am inspirational - I am "special needs" but don't act it.  Without the wheels, I can scoot.  With the wheels, there's no stopping me.  

Hoping to find a home with a family who loves my silky soft fur, my soft eyes and my "can do" attitude.  Oh, I will also need a ramp to the backyard if there are stairs.  But I'm worth it!

All Great Pyrenees require a fenced-in yard (at least four foot high). If you have questions about the breed or our adoption policies and procedures, please go to our website at www.agprescue.org. There's plenty of good information about the breed on our website - Pyrs aren't a breed for everyone!

animal.description:
Meet our Michael!
It'll be 2 years in December he joined us from a high kill shelter here in Ohio.  We are lucky the warden was fired before he could put our boy down. Michael was hurting from his severe neglect and wasn't the friendliest with the shelter folks but then they didn't understand a dog not feeling good and full of fear. 
He joined us with tumors (benign) , decaying teeth, anaemic from flea infestation, and a severe skin infection on most of his body. He could not get better till we took him to a specialist that diagnosed him with a thyroid condition.  He is now doing so much better on his medication and we have it under control. 
As he gets older he needs a quiet home. The current foster home is too busy for our guy, and he is acting up with the other dogs.  He is a typical Eskie senior wanting a peaceful home, and to be the center of your life, your attention, and your love.
We are looking to either adopt this soon to be 12 year old senior, or find him a new foster home to make him happy.
Please email us at ohioeskierescue@outlook.com if interested on adopting or fostering.   If fostering we will go over the requirements and we will pay for all his needs.  We would prefer someone locally, near Cincinnati, Ohio or a Vet that will work with us on cost.  We will not ship him to anyone. You would have to come to Ohio so we can meet you.

animal.description:
This handsome boy is Shane. He was labeled as a Pitbull and was facing euthanasia at animal control because of the BSL placed in Springfield. Thanks to our supporters, we were able to save Shane,  giving him a second chance at life! Shane is a five year old American Pit Bull Terrier/Border Collie mix. Shane makes it a point to enjoy every day to the fullest. He loves going for hikes and is always up for a new adventure. He knows basic commands and is a very smart boy. Shane would do best in an active home, with an adopter who has plenty of time to spend with him. He could be a great agility dog! Shane’s currently enjoying life at the C.A.R.E. Sanctuary while waiting for his perfect home.


All C.A.R.E rescue dogs are fully vaccinated, heart-worm tested, spayed/neutered, and dogs are microchipped! So all you need to provide is the love.

Fill out an adoption application here: http://www.carerescue.org/dog-adoption

Our adoption fee is a minimum $100 tax deductible donation. All donations are used for rescue and medical care of animals in need. If you don't have room to take home a pet but want to support our efforts to save animals in need, please consider making a donation. We are not city or state funded and rely solely on private donations that allow us to continue saving lives.

To learn more about us or to give a life saving donation please visit http://www.carerescue.org

Hey, guys!  My name is Pita.  I have been with TIRR Rescue for a while now.
?
My mom brought me to TIRR Rescue because she could no longer keep me.  She tried everything she could before giving me up, but she finally decided the best choice was to leave me in the care of TIRR Rescue and let them find me a forever home.
?
All of my original pack mates are gone, and I now hang with Deuce.  We've had a couple of other dogs in our pack, but they've been adopted, so it's just Deuce and me.  Deuce likes to think he's the boss, but we all know I'm the real alpha in this neck of the woods.  So long as everyone plays nice and no one bugs me, I get along pretty well with other dogs.  You should come see for yourself!

PERSONALITY:
Pita is a sweet dog who loves to play and cuddle with her people.  She gets along well with other dogs, but she can be a bit bossy at times.  Pita loves to dig and will need a sandbox or play area where she can do so to her heart's content without ruining the yard.

Sammy is a sweet girl that came from a life of neglect. When she first arrived at H4H, she was emaciated, had an old front leg break, no hair and heartworms. Her adopter must be willing to do a "go home session" with her trainer. While Sammy has shown no agression towards kids or dogs, we feel she'd do best in a home without kids or other animals. animal.description:
Macha in a Nutshell

Because of abuse and almost being starved to death, I am a miracle girl!
I'm bossy...but in a funny way that will keep you laughing.
My hair never grew back all the way so my chest and tummy are naked...but my foster mom tells me I'm so beautiful I don't need much hair.
I will drink from your cup if you leave it sitting for me. (Coca-Cola is a favorite)...but I'm trying to save you from drinking too many calories.
I will jump up and steal food from your hand...but (again) I'm trying to help you not eat too many calories.

I'm a handful in the funniest ways.
That's okay. I've earned it after what I've been through. A human tried to starve me to death and I LIVED instead. So, my life is being lived on my own terms. I'm currently interviewing humans to see who is good enough to love me forever!

YOU CAN SPONSOR MACHA'S CARE IN RESCUE BY CLICKING ON THE SPONSOR BUTTON ON THIS PAGE or DIRECTLY ON THE RESCUE'S WEBSITE: www.onmywayhomerescue.com. Thank you so very much for caring and supporting our rescue mission!

animal.description: You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Savannah is a female Pit Bull Terrier mix rescued in Georgia. Our veterinary partner estimates that Savannah was born in 2016. We received the plea for help when she had been spayed at the shelter, and had somehow managed to break her spay stitches. This allowed her intestines to come through the incision site, and she was in critical condition and needed emergency surgery to repair the site. Savannah has been all fixed up and she is now doing well. Savannah is a sweet pup who is great with people of all ages. She must be the only dog in the home, and if there is another dog in the home (which we don't recommend), Savannah cannot be crated. Otherwise, Savannah does great in a crate! She currently sleeps all night in her crate and will rocket into the crate from anywhere in her foster home in response to the "Crate Up" command! She will also go into her open crate with a toy or snack and happily hang out there. Savannah is an excellent listener who will make a great companion! She is housetrained, knows basic commands and not destructive. She is easily overwhelmed with groups of dogs, and cannot visit dog parks. She seems to be okay on leash when there is one other dog around. Savannah will need a family who understands and accepts her issues with other dogs. If you can provide a stable, loving home for Savannah and would like to adopt her, please put your application in here: http://www.rescuedogsrocknyc.org

Need someone who will love and protect you? I’m your guy.

Hey there, I’m Fergus. I’m here to ask you to come meet me. It may take a little bit, but if you’re good I may choose you to go home with. That’s the way it works right? I’ll make a great addition to your family, promise. Look, I’m located at Shaw PBR in Columbus, MS.

animal.description:
"BE SURE TO WATCH MY VIDEO!" 

Date of birth: 12/2014

12/17/2020: Vinny is an adorable Pit Bull mix. He is 6 years old and weighs 77 lbs. He's sweet, silly and affectionate. He loves treats and dog toys, and he’s a clown when he’s playing with a toy! 

• He loves to play fetch and run around in the yard. A fenced yard would be ideal, otherwise we think he’d do okay in a home where he got lots of walks and toys to play with. 

• He’s a strong guy so needs someone who can handle his strength on walks. 

• He gets along with many other dogs, and loves to play in the yard with other dogs. If you have a dog we’d ask you to make an appointment to bring your dog in to meet Vinny to see if they could be buddies.

• Vinny was mistreated in the past. He was scared and had a lot of wounds when he first came to us, including an ear that was horribly torn up and needed surgery. He’s still a little sensitive about his ear. He can be a little head shy at times if you reach for his head, or if someone waves their hand while talking he’ll flinch.  He will likely need a little time to settle into a new home and become comfortable and feel safe. He’s a very sensitive and sweet guy. 

• Vinny loves treats, and he does well meeting new people especially if they have a tasty snack to offer him! Obedience classes would be fun for him since he loves treats, and boost his confidence.  

• Vinny likes kids and we think he’d do well living in a home with teenagers, who understand that he is sensitive. Little kids making a lot of noise and quick movements would startle him. 

• Vinny needs a home without cats.

• Vinny keeps his kennel clean and he’s not very vocal. He has been neutered, vaccinated, microchipped and tested for heartworms. He’s an absolute sweetheart and silly guy who’s been thru a lot and deserves a loving home. 

MORE ON ADOPTING OUR DOGS... 

> COVID-19 UPDATE: PLEASE SUBMIT AN ONLINE ADOPTION APPLICATION AND A MEMBER OF OUR ADOPTIONS TEAM WILL REACH OUT TO YOU. Please visit our web site at HSGKC.ORG for an adoption application, our current COVID-19 adoption protocol, and other adoption info.  

> If you decide you'd like to adopt one of the pets you meet, we reserve the pet for you but we generally don't send the pet home with you that day. We’ll instead schedule a pick up date and time that’s convenient for you.   

> Our goal is to send you home with a healthy pet and any information and support you may need to help your new pet adjust to his or her new home.  All of our dogs & puppies have been spayed or neutered, vaccinated, microchipped, dewormed, treated for fleas & ticks, tested for heartworms (7 mo. and over), and are on monthly heartworm preventative. Puppies who are too young to receive all the necessary puppy boosters and/or first rabies shot may be brought back to us for those vaccines at no extra charge. You will also receive a leash, collar, coupons for pet supplies and services, toys, and educational materials. And we'll give your dog a bath before he or she goes home! 

> Please note that we prefer and may require a fenced yard for many of our dogs.  Exceptions are made on an individual basis depending on the dog's needs, the person's dog experience, the dog's and person's activity levels, home environment and other factors. 

Thank you for searching for a shelter pet!

Phone: 913.596.1000 ext. 113

animal.description:
MEET GEORGE 4!! **Please Note: This is a courtesy post for another rescue; different adoption fees/policy apply.

George is a very sweet boy and will love whoever gives him his forever home! He
enjoys being outdoors and going on hikes. He is already trained in trail etiquette
and basic commands (sit, stay, lay down, come). He is a fast learner and would
benefit from further training in a home and in public.

George unfortunately first came to YHS on a bite quarantine. He becomes protective of his home so when a neighbor teenager entered the house unexpectedly, he bit him on the calf. Our behavior department worked with him some but never saw any of these behaviors at our shelter. He is timid in this environment but quickly learned basic commands and how to walk on a leash well. Our volunteers enjoyed taking him on a hiking trail that runs adjacent to our facility. He was adopted out but has unfortunately returned to us a second time on bite quarantine. His adopters informed us that he was a bolter and would run out the door at any opportunity. One of these bolting episodes led to him biting a teenager on a bike, again on the calf. We believe that with training and the proper adopter who will continue training and working on his various issues, he will make a very good dog.

For more information or to meet this pet, please complete an application or send email to info@underdogaz.com

If you're reading this via a pet-search site, please view this pet's page

at www.UnderdogAZ.com/animals

animal.description:
Emesto is a great little guy! Just 2-years old now, he's potty trained and has been neutered. He loves to play with my other dogs, and he is always up for a good wrestling session. Emesto is great with my cats except he likes to eat their food when he has the opportunity.

He's very shy and has some fear-based tendencies. He does not like strangers coming into his home and has nipped at visitors even though he may be already familiar with them. Because of his fear, no children is a requirement for him.

Emesto has separation anxiety when we leave the house and does not do well in a crate. He tears up his bed and the plastic crate liner, so we had to come up with a different solution for him. He has many dog friends here so we know dog companionship is not an issue. We've ended up separating him in our foyer with very little in there that he can damage. He does scratch at the metal door into the garage but has done little damage other than that.

A home with a fenced yard is also needed. He had excess energy he needs to run off, and he loves hanging out in the yard. So a home with a secure fence is needed

He comes when called and is quite obedient, and he's a great size at 30-pounds and is a bit of a low rider. Emesto also has these enormous ears that stand straight up most of the time. We call him Reilly after Radar O'Reilly on MASH. He's really just adorable!!

He would love to find a forever home and experience the security and happiness that comes along with that forever home.

An Adoption Application for this dog can be found and submitted online at http://www.angelsrescue.org/adopt/adoption-forms

For inquiries, email inquiry@angelsrescue.org

Please be sure to like our Facebook page https://www.facebook.com/angelsrescue.

animal.description:
Update on Beau. After consulting with a trainer, it does appear that Beau is mostly if not all Anatolian Shepherd. He is going to need a home that has experience with livestock guarding breeds and room for him to run. He does get along well with other dogs and cats too. He will not do well with small children as he does not like when small children are loud and jumpy. He can also be protective of his home when his family is not home. He does get very attached to his family and will do best in a home without a lot of traffic and is willing to put him away when they have visitors. While he is very friendly with everyone outside the home, he is an Anatolian and bred to guard his home. Knowledge of this breed is best for this boy. Beau is pretty much a big teddy bear with his family and is very well behaved in the house. His lumps are just fatty lipomas according to the cytology and our vet says they do not need any further treatment. 

Beau came to us from a shelter in Alabama. He was found as a stray and no one came to claim him. He is a very big and sweet boy. He is 103 pounds and appears to be a lab, hound with maybe something else in him too. Beau has definitely lived in a home before. He is housebroken and even gets along very well with cats. He really does seem to like being with cats and he does also seem to get along very well with other dogs. We think he is about 5-7 years old and he is very much a gentle giant. He does have some weird lumps that we have the vet checking out and all his bloodwork has come back normal. So we think this maybe normal for him. He is neutered, up to date with vaccines, microchipped and heartworm and Lyme negtive. His adoption fee is $200.00. If you are interested in adopting Beau, please visit our website www.LHARinc.org go to Adopt and complete the dog adoption application.

animal.description:
Marla was born in May of 2018. She is a very sweet girl, working on some confidence in her new foster home. Marla is a beautiful girl that is looking for a patient, consistent owner. She is looking for a home that is able to provide her with stability to help her overcome her fears and help get her on the right track! Marla would love to live in a new home as an only dog but with the proper intro, she could potentially be OK! She is reactive to dogs in general and would need multiple visits with her new adopter. She would, however, do best in a home with no children. Young children and other high strung dogs really stress her out. Marla also needs a 6 foot fence because she can clear a 4 foot fence with no problems. With lots of structure, positive reinforcement, and the help of a trainer, we are confident that Marla will blossom into a great companion. If you think Marla would be a great addition to your family, please fill out an application to meet this sweet girl!

The suggested adoption donation for Marla is $300, which is TAX
DEDUCTIBLE, and goes toward providing supportive services to animals in
the home, as well as the high cost of vetting our dogs in rescue. If you would
like to welcome Marla into your home, please begin by submitting our Adoption

animal.description:
Chuck/Chuckles is an amazing boy.  As you can see from his pictures he has been through a lot!  He was a stray that was found hanging over someone's picket fence.  He stayed there over night until someone finally found him and was able to lift him off the fence.  A wonderful volunteer brought him to us and we were unsure he would ever walk again. He didn't walk for 3 days, it scared us so bad.  After the initially 3 days he started to get movement back.  It was slow going since he was so swollen and bruised.  We took him to the vet and we found a pellet in one of his back legs and that he is heartworm positive.  We had the pellet removed and he underwent an extensive neuter procedure and had his teeth cleaned.  Chuck is undergoing the slow kill method for his heartworms so that he is not put under any stress during treatment.  The wound in the picture was from hanging on the fence over night.  It took about 2.5 months to heal and close up completely.  Now Chuck in 100% healed and is living a happy life waiting for his forever family to find him.  Through all that he has been through Chuck is so loving and forgiving.  He is a bit demanding for attention. He will push his way in to get love.  He gets along well with all sizes of dogs.  He is just starting to open up and play with the dogs at his foster home.  He loves to just lay around and relax.  

If you are interested in coming to meet or adopting Chuck please visit our website at www.shannonfarmz.com and fill out an adoption application.  You won't regret meeting this sweet boy!!!

animal.description:
Our Marbles is a comical character! He came to us from a southern rescue whose volunteers were charmed by his striking appearance, and beautiful merle colors. Marbles seems to be an Australian Cattle Dog, but his short, flat coat and head shape suggests some Lab DNA.

After his owners gave up on him, Marbles was left in a Virginia shelter without a strong adoption program. His options became tragically limited, so we invited him to Connecticut. Clearly, Marbles is is a double dose of working dog, so he definitely needs an active lifestyle and a job. Herders are hardwired to work, and if his adopters do not give Marbles a job, he will practice his herding skills within the household. A bored, frustrated herding dog is a recipe for mayhem.

Exercise and obedience training are the keys to managing the Herding breeds. Marbles is a high-energy dog, who would make a great running, walking or hiking partner. He's built for speed, but will adjust his pace to suit his handler. He needs at least three brisk daily leash walks, in addition to focused playtime. Adopters can increase the intensity of a walk by outfitting Marbles with a dog backpack, loaded with water, and a collapsable bowl. At each rest and water stop, Marbles will feel like he's got a job and will be quite proud of himself.

Obedience training is essential to meeting the needs of a Herding dog. Marbles already knows all of his basic obedience commands, and has passed many of his Canine Good Citizenship tests. Structure and obedience work go a long way in providing him the mental and physical challenges that he needs. Adopters should be prepared to troubleshoot things that come up with Marbles, as he transitions to a new environment.

Marbles is best suited to an active adult home, with a dog savvy single or couple, who have the time and energy to give him his daily exercise. Tranquility and calm suit Marbles best. In a chaotic, hectic environment he becomes anxious and demonstrates herding behavior in order to maintain social order. In a calm environment, Marbles relaxes and enjoys quiet time with his people. Kids and cats may provide too much stimulation, but Marbles could easily join a multi-dog home, with an energy compatible, well socialized dog.

Marbles has good house manners and is house trained and crate trained, although adopters should expect to troubleshoot a few accidents during his transition to a new routine. He is in excellent health, has been neutered. He has been vaccinated for Rabies, DHLPPC (distemper, hepatitis, leptospirosis, parvo, parainfluenza and coronavirus), He has been boostered as needed. He has had the 4dx test: negative for heartworm, lyme, earlichia and anaplasmosis. If you are interested in Marbles, please write to Denise@eskiesonline.com or call/text Denise at 860-908-9738 for more info.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Hi, my name is Sassy and I'm ready for my forever home. My first family abandoned me when I was a baby, so I don't like being left alone. I'm very energetic, active, curious, lovable, sensitive and absolutely adorable. I'm a smart girl, who knows some basics obedience. However, obedience classes would really be a good idea for me and my new family. I love having canine brothers and sisters to play with. Right now, I have three sisters and a brother. I'm the youngest, but I'm bigger than everybody. We have a blast running, wrestling, and chasing toys during the day. At night, we cuddle up and take a short break from the excitement. I've never had any human brothers or sisters, but I'm sure I'd like them as long as they are older and know the proper way to play with me. I DON'T like my tail or ears pulled, and please don't touch my behind. Did I mention I don't like to be left alone? I get bored quickly, and I just might get into something I shouldn't. So, it's best to keep an eye on me, and crate me when no one is home. Afterall, I'm still a kid and I'm still learning. Please be patient with me, and I'll grow up to be the best dog ever. I don't care much for being hugged, but I like giving hugs. If you're looking for a special little girl, who will love you unconditionally and will fit right in with your other doggies, I just might be that girl. Don't forget to check out all of my gorgeous photos and my amazing video.

Please contact
app@aarfhouston.org
for more information about this dog.

You can apply online by clicking on

Application

. Once your application is approved, we will schedule a meet and greet at one of our adoption events.

Thank you for considering a rescue!

The adoption fee includes vaccinations, Bordetella, de-worming, rabies, spay/neuter and microchip. There is a an additional $12.99 fee for Home Again for a lifetime registration of the microchip.
Puppies cannot be adopted outside of the Houston area until they are spay/neutered after they are 4 months old. It is against the law in the State of Texas for a rescue not to be sterilized so we have to make sure it gets completed and that we have record of it.
NOTE: In our bios, we provide information based on our volunteer's experience with a particular dog; such as temperament, training, and ability to get along with others.

animal.description: Zeke is a handsome Rotti/Lab mix who is looking for a home of his own after his owner sadly passed away. He is approximately 6.5 years old and a big strong boy at just under 80 lbs. This canine gentleman is house trained, well behaved in the home, does not mind being left alone, walks well on a leash and has a good understanding of basic commands. Zeke is gentle, cuddly and super affectionate with his people but true to his breed, can be territorial when strangers enter his home or yard; he can be nervous of people when he first meets them but warms up quickly and once he knows you he will greet you like a long-lost friend! A home that has experience with these guardian breed traits would be ideal for him. Zeke also needs some work on handling, in particular his feet and at the vet's, and requires a patient and knowledgeable owner who will continue the work his foster home has been doing to desensitize him, using only positive methods since he does not respond well to harsh corrections. This special boy has so much potential and is going to make a great addition to the right family. At this time we are looking for an adult family who have same (or similar) breed experience where he will be the only animal in the home.  Due to some behavioral issues Zeke requires a fully fenced backyard and is not suitable for condo/apartment living.

BACKGROUND:  Tiny, precious Lollipop came to us from a kill shelter, where she had been picked up as a stray.  She weighs only 13 pounds and is just adorable. Lollipop has been living quite the pampered life with her foster parents Barbara and Drew, where Barbara spends time each day taking great care of Lolli.

Please email the completed application to newleashrescue2018@gmail.com

Meet Kenny...a 1-2 year old beagle mix (long body, low rider with an underbite).  Kenny was surrendered by a family who was moving, and he was terribly frightened in the shelter.  Oftentimes a frightened dog in the shelter relaxes in home foster care, but Kenny took longer than most and would run and hide.  We have been celebrating his progress in baby steps.  He is finally looking happy and alert, tolerating eye contact, and wagging his tail.  He takes his cues from the other dogs, and he now runs up to his foster mom with the pack to greet her and touches his nose to her hand.  He understands “kennel up” for meal time and enters his crate on his own with encouragement (the edible kind).  He loves treats and is just starting to take them by hand.  Kenny is conflicted about touch, as he is not keen to be handled, yet he seems to enjoy a little bit of scratching and petting now when he is in his crate.  He does not go outside yet, as he is a very high flight risk, and he is making nice progress with pad training.  True to his breed, Kenny can be vocal, so he is not an apartment dog.  He is a delightful boy who needs a patient, understanding, experienced adopter who is willing to meet him where he is at now.  He would thrive in a quieter environment with at least one other dog companion and needs a fenced in yard.  

Adoption fee is $350.00 + tax (no checks)

Foster to contact:  Sara - 651-260-3774 or sara.fostermom@gmail.com

This dog will not be at our adoption event at the Woodbury PetSmart on Saturday from 11-2, so contact his foster to learn more. 

Our fosters do the best they can to provide all information about the animal's background and temperament while in foster care in their home. An adopters routine and home environment is likely going to be different than that in their foster home. 

Sometimes there is more that comes out about a dog's personality once they have been able to settle in a home and truly become comfortable. There are great articles out there written about the different stages a pet goes through after adoption, discussing transitions that happen at 3 days, 3 weeks, and 3 months. We highly recommend reading about this - it will help you understand the transition your new pet goes through.

Shayla is young, silly, and a spaz! I spend so much time laughing at this girl! I doubt this girl is much past her first birthday and the fact that she is heart worm positive just blows my mind! ETPBR will treat her HWs prior to finalizing her adoption. Shayla is spayed and vaccinated We will micro chip her in the next few days. She loves other dogs and people. She needs some manners and we will work on that... Meanwhile Shayla needs a foster home to help us get her thru her heart worm treatment. If that foster home were to be a foster to adopt home...well all the better. If you have room in your heart and home for this clown, please fill out the on-line application at www.etnpitbullrescue.orgEast TN Pit Bull Rescue adopts out to companion homes only. Adoptions require an application that is verified, a meeting that includes ALL members of the household, a home visit, and a trial period. We do not place our dogs in homes with unaltered pets or homes that have pets but do not have a vet. All of our dogs are placed as inside pets, spayed/neutered, micro chipped, vaccinations current, and HW- or treated within the last 6 months for heart worms by our vet. Adoption fees start at $150 for adults and $200 for pups. If you are interested in offering this pet a responsible and loving home, please fill out the on-line application at www.etnpitbullrescue.org. East TN Pit Bull Rescue is a Tennessee Non-profit corporation with 501(c)(3) status. Your donations to sponsor pets are tax deductible. If you would like to sponsor this pet, please go to www.paypal.com and make a donation to donations@etnpitbullrescue.org OR contact Butler's Animal Clinic at 865-531-7311 to make a donation on the East TN Pit Bull Rescue Account. Just say sit and he gladly obeys, especially if a treat is involved.  He'd love to learn more tricks, maybe you could be the one to teach him. It would be fun!   This handsome boy delights in going for rides and his big ol' smilie face hanging out the window is proof!  Domino will be all you need as he should be your only pet, and with older considerate children only.  Est. birthdate is Aug. 2013,  about 62 lbs. vetted, neutered, microchipped, and ready to be your big baby for life!  Adoption fee $250.00.
Please submit an adoption application, https://www.shelterluv.com/matchme/adopt/TBTR/Dog

animal.description:
Shelby is believed to be a Labrador-Pittie mix, which is honestly a dream combination; the fun of a Labrador and the smushy cuddles of a pitty! Her webbed paws are hilariously big for her body, and she lives for a summer swim! Shelby is the type of dog that you’ll need an extra 5 minutes with. While we don’t know the details of her past, we do know that she had enough experiences with NC’s finest to distrust humans. Shelby might initially bark or do a little nervous jig, but this sweet girl emerges in just a few minutes and she is worth the wait!

Now that we’ve tried to sell you on Shelby, it’s YOUR turn to sell yourself TO Shelby. Shelby will need three or more of the following adopter qualities before she unpacks her bags and calls it home:
1) Seven bedroom mansion by the lake, complete with pool and dock for optimal swimming opportunity (okay, a walk to the river or lake will also do...we guess)
2) Netflix subscription. Shelby is currently rewatching The Office for the 8th time
3) Comfy bed to allow for optimal cuddles
4) TREATS. All of the treats.
5) A canine companion for company and cardio (Wrestlemania ??)
6) A human with ideal arm strength for belly scratches and leg strength for those lake walks (see item 
7) Toys. We’re talking squeaky, fluffy, rope, rubber, whatever!
 

Shelby’s quote: “Forever is just a word until someone comes along and gives it meaning. Help me find my forever.”

If you are interested in adopting Shelby, please visit www.pincdogrescue.com/adopt and submit an adoption application. You will also find our adoption process listed on that page.

animal.description:
Adoption Fee:  $100
Fostered in Houma, Louisiana
Age:  12 years
Weight:  13 lbs.

9/24/20 - It's been a long time since Pacino has updated you and that's because he has been so busy loving life.  Although he is getting older, not much has changed in his energy department and as you can see by his new pics, he doesn't look any older.  His foster mom says he still acts as if he is 6.  He did just start some new medicine though.  It's called Proin.  Seems Pacino is having trouble tinkling when he is sleeping.  The vet is trying this to see if will help.  Foster mom is noticing that his eyesight and hearing are lacking a little, but that happens to everyone with age.

He also takes Phenobarbital for seizures and, thankfully, hasn't had any seizures since he's been on the medicine.  He takes 1 15 mg pill twice daily.

He doesn't really play with any of the other dogs in his foster home.  He does love car rides and going for walks.  He loves breakfast and supper time and is a very fast eater

Other than that, Pacino is a happy, healthy boy and if you ask him, he has many years left.  Want to give an older guy a happy home?  Pacino loves everyone and even though he loves foster mom, he wouldn't mind changing addresses if it would give him a last name.

7/15/19 - Pacino is a sweetheart of a guy.  He definitely doesn't act, look or feel his age.  The guy seems more like 7 years old.  He is a bigger, longer bodied boy, but still small enough to pick up and love.  He loves giving kisses and is very in tune with his people.  Since his bladder stone surgery, he eats a prescription diet.  If there are other pups in the home, Pacino would have to be put up to eat since he is food aggressive with other dogs.  We aren't sure where this stemmed from, but it is an easy fix, just put in a room to eat or a crate.  If there aren't any other dogs in the home, which Pacino would absolutely love, there is no need to put him up while eating.  He is fine with the other dogs all other times, so could co-exist or be the only big baby.  We have just noticed a growth on Pacino's leg by his front left shoulder, and will be getting it checked out and removed soon, along with a tiny sty on the inside of his bottom eyelid.  Pacino would be a great addition to a laid back home with or without dogs where he can be loved and give love.

6/21/19 - Pacino has been in his foster home for a while now and wants to give everyone an update.  You would not be able to guess his age if you met him because he acts so young at heart and has energy to burn.  His legs are like springs and he can bounce very high.  He needs a big secure yard to run and play in and owners that can watch him when the front door is open since he is very curious and tempted to run.  The perfect home for Pacino would be where he could be the only pup or with one other calm dog since he loves getting a lot of attention.  He does have Napoleon tendencies at feeding time, so he eats separately and isn’t let out until everyone is finished so as not to have any fights.

Please give Pacino a chance at a home where he is the main man and he will not disappoint you.

3/20/19 - Now since I am feeling better, foster mom said that it is time for me to tell the world about myself.  Well, my name is Pacino, as in Al Pacino.  My previous mom could not keep me any longer due to life changes, so my new foster mom stepped in to give me a place to call my own until she could find me my real home.  Shortly after coming to live with her, she realized I had bladder stones and needed immediate surgery.  That was done and now I feel so much better.  I will have to stay on a prescription diet food (Royal Canin Urinary SO hard food) from now on so they won’t return, but it’s fine because I like my new food.  

I eat twice daily and need to eat alone.  I tend to be a bit of a terminator if another dog comes around while I am trying to enjoy by kibble.  So, it’s much easier if I just eat alone and stay up until all the other furbabies are finished eating.

I’m ok around children as long as they are older and don’t get too chaotic or want to pull on my ears or tail.  And I do like to give the humans, old or young, kisses.
I would love to sleep in bed with my humans and I promise I will not take up too much of the bed or covers.

I get very attached to my humans and love getting and giving attention.  I can also be a great coach potato if you want to snuggle and cuddle for some movies.  I also like playing with toys.  My potty training is coming along, and I will use pee pads, but foster mom still catches me marking at times.  So, I’m not perfect.

I will bark when I’m excite or when the other dogs bark, it isn’t crazy obsessive.  I’m a little timid around the vacuum cleaner but getting more used to it.  I have very strong legs and can jump on the furniture to be with you.

I do have terrier in me, so I will have to be put up or picked up if someone is at the door because I will take that opportunity to run off.  The unknown just looks so exciting.

I wouldn’t mind another doggy to play with, but they shouldn’t be too rough because I can get offended easily.  I might be 10 years old, but I don’t know it and I have energy to play.  That doesn’t mean that I can turn right around and nap or cuddle with my humans.

I just an all-around great boy that is in the prime of my life.  I’m up for a walk, a nap or basically whatever you want.  First, you have to apply to adopt me and then we can discuss adventures.

2/24/19 - Thanks to all of you, Pacino had his bladder stone surgery Friday and is doing well.  We are so happy for this little man.  His foster mom picked him up yesterday and its as if he never had surgery.  It's amazing what these babies can endure.  He will have a recheck in about a week to have a urinalysis and see if all is well, then schedule his dental and he will get a microchip at that time.  Pacino said to tell everyone thank you and we will be posting a bio soon to tell about his personality very soon.

2/14/19 - Pacino needs immediate surgery because he is in need of surgery.  He has 1 large bladder stone in his bladder.  Please consider donating to Pacino so we can get him comfortable.  He was surrendered by his owner because she did not have time for him.  He is in a foster home now and ready to have surgery and start feeling better.  PLEASE HELP US HELP PACINO!!!

animal.description:
Hi there! My name is Jebb. I'm a neutered male Shih Tzu, 5 years old (approx. DOB 1/1/2016), wgt 15.5 lbs., neutered, micro-chipped, rabies, heartworm tested, distemper, and wormed. 

My past is unknown. When I was rescued from the streets, I suffered from a degenerative retinal disease that was progressive, rendering me blind, therefore, both my eyes were surgically removed in February 2019. I am also hard of hearing but can hear loud sounds. I have adapted well to my blindness. I am a lover, a character with so much love and life to offer you. I love tummy rubs, snuggling, cuddling with you in bed, showering your face with kisses, and walks on a leash. I can navigate a house exceptionally well and can learn the layout of a new home really fast! I can get up on a couch or chair by myself but my favorite place to chill is in a dog bed. I am such a happy little boy nothing can stop me from learning new things. I get along well in my foster home with a cat and three other dogs.

I need a calm home and don't do well with young children that do not understand that I am blind and who may repeatedly and/or unexpectedly grab at me. This stresses me out and gives me anxiety.  I also require minimal time alone. If not in a secure, fenced outdoor area, I will need to be leashed and have my person with me for guidance.

My adoption fee $250.00
For information about me you can email my foster mom directly at cacollins46@gmail.com. To fill out a pre-adopt application please cut and paste the following URL, https://tinyurl/com/LETS-PRE-ADOPT-APP into your browser.  Potential adopters will be contacted to arrange a meet and greet at Pet Supplies Plus 2649 E. Grand River, Howell, MI.

No out of state adoptions
